Inheritance is a fundamental Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) mechanism in Java where a new class (called the subclass or child class) acquires the properties (fields) and behaviors (methods) of an existing class (called the superclass or parent class). It is implemented using the extends keyword.

Inheritance establishes an IS-A relationship between classes. For example, a Dog IS-A Animal, so Dog can inherit from Animal.

Simple Example:
class Animal {
    String name;
    void eat() {
        System.out.println(name + " is eating.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println(name + " is barking.");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.name = "Buddy";
        d.eat();   // Inherited from Animal
        d.bark();  // Defined in Dog
    }
}

Output:
Buddy is eating.
Buddy is barking.

Key points:
- Dog inherits the name field and eat() method from Animal automatically
- Dog adds its own method bark()
- The Dog object can access both inherited and its own methods
- Java supports single inheritance only (one parent class per subclass)
- Multiple inheritance is achieved through interfaces

Encapsulation is an OOP principle that bundles data (attributes/fields) and the methods that operate on that data into a single unit (class), while restricting direct access to the fields from outside the class. It is also called data hiding.

Java achieves encapsulation through:

1. DECLARING FIELDS AS PRIVATE: This prevents direct access from outside the class.

2. PROVIDING PUBLIC GETTER AND SETTER METHODS: These methods provide controlled access to the private fields.

Example:
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;  // private - cannot be accessed directly
    private String owner;

    // Getter
    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    // Setter with validation
    public void setBalance(double amount) {
        if (amount >= 0) {
            this.balance = amount;
        }
    }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
        }
    }
}

In this example:
- balance is private, so no one can do: account.balance = -1000
- The setter validates the input before updating
- The deposit method adds business logic
- Internal state is protected from invalid modifications

Benefits:
- Data integrity: Invalid values are prevented by validation in setters
- Flexibility: Internal representation can change without affecting external code
- Debugging: All access goes through methods, making bugs easier to trace

ABSTRACT CLASS vs INTERFACE in Java:

1. METHODS:
- Abstract class: Can have both abstract methods (no body) AND concrete methods (with body)
- Interface: Can only have abstract methods (prior to Java 8). From Java 8, interfaces can have default and static methods with bodies.

2. CONSTRUCTORS:
- Abstract class: Can have constructors
- Interface: Cannot have constructors

3. INHERITANCE:
- Abstract class: A class can extend only ONE abstract class (single inheritance)
- Interface: A class can implement MULTIPLE interfaces (multiple inheritance of type)

4. KEYWORDS:
- Abstract class: Uses extends keyword
- Interface: Uses implements keyword

5. FIELDS:
- Abstract class: Can have any type of fields (instance variables)
- Interface: All fields are implicitly public, static, and final (constants)

6. ACCESS MODIFIERS:
- Abstract class: Methods can have any access modifier
- Interface: Methods are implicitly public (prior to Java 9)

Example:
abstract class Shape {
    String color;
    abstract double area();  // abstract method
    void displayColor() {   // concrete method
        System.out.println("Color: " + color);
    }
}

interface Drawable {
    void draw();  // abstract method
    default void resize() {  // default method (Java 8+)
        System.out.println("Resizing...");
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape implements Drawable {
    double radius;
    double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing circle"); }
}

Use abstract class when classes share common state and behavior. Use interface when defining a contract that unrelated classes must follow.

METHOD OVERLOADING vs METHOD OVERRIDING:

METHOD OVERLOADING (Compile-time Polymorphism):
- Same method name, DIFFERENT parameter list (different number, type, or order of parameters)
- Occurs within the SAME class
- Resolved at COMPILE TIME (compiler decides which method to call)
- No inheritance required
- Return type can be different

public class Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }  // overloaded
    int add(int a, int b, int c) { return a + b + c; }  // overloaded
}

METHOD OVERRIDING (Runtime Polymorphism):
- Same method name AND same parameter list (same signature)
- Occurs in a SUBCLASS redefining a method from its PARENT class
- Resolved at RUNTIME (JVM decides which method to call based on object type)
- Requires inheritance (IS-A relationship)
- Return type must be the same or a subtype (covariant)
- Use @Override annotation for compile-time checking

class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Some sound"); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() { System.out.println("Bark"); }
}

Key Differences:
1. Parameters: Overloading has different params; overriding has same params
2. Inheritance: Overloading needs no inheritance; overriding requires it
3. Binding: Overloading = compile-time; Overriding = runtime
4. Annotation: @Override is used only for overriding
5. Scope: Overloading is within one class; overriding spans parent-child classes

Polymorphism is a core OOP principle meaning "many forms." It allows objects of different types to be treated through a single interface, where the actual behavior depends on the specific type of the object at runtime.

TWO TYPES OF POLYMORPHISM IN JAVA:

1. COMPILE-TIME POLYMORPHISM (Method Overloading):
The compiler determines which method to call based on the method signature (name + parameters).

class Printer {
    void print(String s) { System.out.println("String: " + s); }
    void print(int n) { System.out.println("Number: " + n); }
    void print(String s, int n) { System.out.println(s + ": " + n); }
}
// The correct print() is chosen at compile time based on argument types.

2. RUNTIME POLYMORPHISM (Method Overriding):
The JVM determines which method to call at runtime based on the actual object type, not the reference type.

class Shape {
    double area() { return 0; }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;
    double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double width, height;
    double area() { return width * height; }
}

// Runtime polymorphism in action:
Shape s1 = new Circle();     // parent reference, child object
Shape s2 = new Rectangle();
System.out.println(s1.area());  // Calls Circle.area() -> πr²
System.out.println(s2.area());  // Calls Rectangle.area() -> w×h

This is called dynamic method dispatch — the JVM looks at the actual object (Circle or Rectangle) to decide which area() to call, even though the reference type is Shape.

Benefits:
- Code flexibility: New subclasses can be added without changing existing code
- Code reusability: Common interface for different types
- Loose coupling: Code works with the parent type, not specific implementations

The super keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the immediate parent class. It is used to access parent class members (fields, methods, constructors) that may be hidden or overridden in the subclass.

THREE USES OF super:

1. ACCESSING PARENT CLASS CONSTRUCTOR:
super() calls the parent class constructor. It must be the first statement in the child constructor.

class Person {
    String name;
    Person(String name) { this.name = name; }
}

class Student extends Person {
    int rollNo;
    Student(String name, int rollNo) {
        super(name);  // calls Person(String name)
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
    }
}

If the parent has a no-arg constructor, Java automatically calls super(). But if the parent only has parameterized constructors, you MUST explicitly call super(args).

2. CALLING OVERRIDDEN PARENT METHOD:
super.method() calls the parent version of a method that has been overridden.

class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Some sound"); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        super.sound();  // calls Animal.sound() first
        System.out.println("Bark");  // then adds own behavior
    }
}
// Output: Some sound\nBark

3. ACCESSING HIDDEN PARENT FIELD:
super.field accesses a parent field when the child has a field with the same name.

class Parent {
    int x = 10;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int x = 20;
    void print() {
        System.out.println(x);      // 20 (child)
        System.out.println(super.x); // 10 (parent)
    }
}

Abstraction is an OOP principle that hides the complex implementation details of a system and exposes only the essential features to the user. The user interacts with the abstract interface without needing to understand the internal workings.

HOW ABSTRACTION IS IMPLEMENTED IN JAVA:

1. ABSTRACT CLASSES (Partial Abstraction):
An abstract class is declared using the abstract keyword. It can contain both abstract methods (no body) and concrete methods (with body). It cannot be instantiated.

abstract class Vehicle {
    String model;

    void displayInfo() {  // concrete method
        System.out.println("Model: " + model);
    }

    abstract void start();  // abstract method - no body
    abstract void stop();   // abstract method - no body
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    void start() { System.out.println("Car engine started"); }
    void stop() { System.out.println("Car engine stopped"); }
}

// Vehicle v = new Vehicle();  // ERROR - cannot instantiate abstract class
Vehicle v = new Car();  // OK - polymorphism
v.start();  // Car engine started

2. INTERFACES (Full Abstraction):
An interface defines a contract that implementing classes must follow. All methods are abstract by default (pre-Java 8).

interface Drawable {
    void draw();  // abstract by default
}

class Circle implements Drawable {
    public void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing circle"); }
}

class Square implements Drawable {
    public void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing square"); }
}

A class can implement multiple interfaces:
class Shape implements Drawable, Resizable {
    // must implement methods from both interfaces
}

Encapsulation is important in OOP design for several key reasons:

1. DATA PROTECTION: By making fields private, encapsulation prevents external code from directly modifying object state. This prevents accidental corruption of data. For example, a bank account balance cannot be set to a negative value by external code.

2. FLEXIBILITY AND MAINTAINABILITY: Internal implementation can change without affecting code that uses the class. If a class stores data differently internally, as long as the public methods (getters/setters) remain the same, no external code needs to change.

3. DATA VALIDATION: Setters can include validation logic to ensure only valid data is stored. For example, a setAge() method can reject negative values or unrealistic ages.

4. EASIER DEBUGGING: Since all access to data goes through methods, it is easier to trace bugs. You can add logging to a setter to see every modification, rather than searching through all code that directly accesses a field.

5. MODULARITY: Each class becomes a self-contained unit with a clear boundary between its public interface and private implementation. This makes the codebase easier to understand and navigate.

6. LOOSE COUPLING: Components interact through well-defined public interfaces rather than internal details. This reduces dependencies and makes the system more modular and easier to test.

Example:
public class Temperature {
    private double celsius;

    public void setCelsius(double c) {
        if (c < -273.15) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Below absolute zero");
        this.celsius = c;
    }

    public double getFahrenheit() {
        return (celsius * 9/5) + 32;
    }
}
// Internal representation (celsius) is hidden. External code uses the public interface.

The final keyword in Java is used to restrict modification. Its role differs depending on what it is applied to:

1. FINAL CLASS:
A class declared as final cannot be extended (subclassed). This prevents inheritance.

final class MathUtils {
    static double square(double x) { return x * x; }
}

// class Extended extends MathUtils {} // COMPILE ERROR - cannot extend final class

Java's String class is final for security — it cannot be subclassed to alter string behavior.

2. FINAL METHOD:
A method declared as final cannot be overridden by subclasses. This preserves the original behavior.

class Parent {
    final void criticalMethod() {
        System.out.println("Original implementation");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    // void criticalMethod() {} // COMPILE ERROR - cannot override final method
}

This is used when the method contains critical logic that must not be changed by subclasses.

3. FINAL VARIABLE:
A variable declared as final can only be assigned once. After assignment, its value cannot change. It becomes a constant.

final int MAX_SIZE = 100;
// MAX_SIZE = 200; // COMPILE ERROR - cannot reassign final variable

For object references, final means the reference cannot point to a different object, but the object's internal state can still change:

final int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
arr[0] = 10;  // OK - modifying contents
// arr = new int[5];  // ERROR - cannot reassign reference

Benefits:
- Security: Prevents subclasses from overriding critical methods
- Immutability: Final variables create constants
- Thread safety: Final fields are safe to share across threads
- Clarity: Signals to other developers that something should not change

Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes (a class cannot extend more than one class) to avoid the diamond problem — ambiguity that arises when two parent classes have the same method. However, Java supports multiple inheritance of type through interfaces.

A class can implement multiple interfaces, thereby inheriting the abstract methods from all of them:

interface Flyable {
    void fly();
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
}

interface Drivable {
    void drive();
}

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable, Drivable {
    public void fly() { System.out.println("Duck is flying"); }
    public void swim() { System.out.println("Duck is swimming"); }
    public void drive() { System.out.println("Duck is driving (somehow)"); }
}

Duck inherits from THREE interfaces and must implement all their methods.

MULTIPLE INHERITANCE OF BEHAVIOR (Java 8+ default methods):

interface A {
    default void show() { System.out.println("From A"); }
}

interface B {
    default void show() { System.out.println("From B"); }
}

// Diamond problem resolved by explicit override:
class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void show() {
        A.super.show();  // explicitly choose A's version
    }
}

Multiple inheritance of STATE is not possible (no multiple extends), but multiple inheritance of TYPE and BEHAVIOR is fully supported through interfaces.

CLASS vs OBJECT in Java:

A CLASS is a blueprint or template that defines the structure (fields) and behavior (methods) that objects of that type will have. It is a logical entity that does not occupy memory for its instance fields.

An OBJECT is a specific instance of a class — a concrete entity created from the blueprint. It occupies memory and holds actual values for the fields defined by the class.

Example:
// CLASS definition (blueprint)
class Car {
    String model;
    int year;

    void start() {
        System.out.println(model + " started");
    }
}

// OBJECT creation (instances)
Car car1 = new Car();  // object 1
car1.model = "Toyota";
car1.year = 2023;

Car car2 = new Car();  // object 2
car2.model = "Honda";
car2.year = 2024;

// Both car1 and car2 are objects of the same class Car
// but they have different states (different model and year values)

KEY DIFFERENCES:
1. Definition: Class = blueprint; Object = instance of that blueprint
2. Memory: Class declaration allocates no instance memory; object creation allocates memory (via new)
3. Quantity: One class can create unlimited objects
4. Existence: Class exists as code; object exists at runtime in memory
5. Creation: Class is defined with class keyword; Object is created with new keyword
6. State: Class defines possible state (fields); Object holds actual state (field values)
7. Nature: Class is a logical entity; Object is a physical entity in heap memory

Getter and setter methods are special methods used in encapsulation to provide controlled access to private fields of a class.

GETTER METHOD (Accessor):
Returns the value of a private field. It has no parameters and returns the field value.

public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // Getter for name
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    // Getter for age
    public int getAge() {
        return age;
    }
}

SETTER METHOD (Mutator):
Assigns a value to a private field. It takes a parameter and returns void (or boolean for success/failure).

public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // Setter for name
    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    // Setter for age with validation
    public void setAge(int age) {
        if (age >= 0 && age <= 150) {
            this.age = age;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid age");
        }
    }
}

Usage:
Person p = new Person();
p.setName("John");  // setter
p.setAge(25);       // setter with validation
System.out.println(p.getName());  // getter -> "John"
System.out.println(p.getAge());   // getter -> 25

Why use them:
1. Data validation: Setter can reject invalid values
2. Read-only fields: Provide getter but no setter
3. Computed values: Getter can calculate and return derived values
4. Logging: Methods can log access for debugging
5. Flexibility: Internal representation can change without breaking external code

Constructors and methods are both blocks of code in a class, but they differ in several important ways:

1. PURPOSE:
- Constructor: Initializes a newly created object. It is called automatically when new is used.
- Method: Performs operations on an already existing object. It is called explicitly.

2. NAME:
- Constructor: Must have the same name as the class
- Method: Can have any valid identifier as its name

3. RETURN TYPE:
- Constructor: Has NO return type (not even void)
- Method: Must have a return type (void if returns nothing)

4. INVOCATION:
- Constructor: Called automatically via the new keyword
- Method: Called explicitly on an object reference (obj.method())

5. OVERLOADING vs OVERRIDING:
- Constructor: Can be overloaded (different parameters) but NOT overridden
- Method: Can be both overloaded and overridden

6. DEFAULT:
- Constructor: Java provides a default no-arg constructor if none is defined
- Method: No default method is provided

Example:
public class Student {
    String name;
    int id;

    // Constructor (same name as class, no return type)
    Student(String name, int id) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
    }

    // Method (different name, has return type)
    public void displayInfo() {
        System.out.println(name + " - " + id);
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

Student s = new Student("Alice", 101);  // constructor called
s.displayInfo();  // method called

The this keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the current object — the instance on which a method or constructor is currently being executed.

PURPOSES OF this:

1. TO DISTINGUISH INSTANCE VARIABLES FROM LOCAL VARIABLES:
When a parameter or local variable has the same name as an instance variable, this resolves the ambiguity.

public class Person {
    String name;

    Person(String name) {
        this.name = name;  // this.name = field, name = parameter
    }

    void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;  // same disambiguation
    }
}

Without this, the line "name = name" would assign the parameter to itself (shadowing).

2. CONSTRUCTOR CHAINING (calling another constructor):
this() with parameters calls another constructor in the same class. It must be the first statement.

public class Student {
    String name;
    int id;

    Student() {
        this("Unknown", 0);  // calls the parameterized constructor
    }

    Student(String name, int id) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
    }
}

3. PASSING THE CURRENT OBJECT:
this can be passed as an argument to other methods.

public class Printer {
    void print(Student s) { System.out.println(s.name); }
}

public class Student {
    String name;
    void sendToPrinter(Printer p) {
        p.print(this);  // passes the current Student object
    }
}

4. RETURNING THE CURRENT OBJECT:
this can be returned for method chaining.

public class Builder {
    int x, y;
    Builder setX(int x) { this.x = x; return this; }
    Builder setY(int y) { this.y = y; return this; }
}
// Used as: new Builder().setX(1).setY(2);

Java supports the following types of inheritance:

1. SINGLE INHERITANCE:
A subclass extends one superclass. This is the simplest form.
class Animal { }
class Dog extends Animal { }

2. MULTILEVEL INHERITANCE:
A chain of inheritance where a class extends another class that itself extends another class.
class GrandParent { }
class Parent extends GrandParent { }
class Child extends Parent { }
// Child inherits from both Parent and GrandParent transitively

3. HIERARCHICAL INHERITANCE:
Multiple subclasses extend the same superclass.
class Vehicle { }
class Car extends Vehicle { }
class Bike extends Vehicle { }
class Truck extends Vehicle { }

4. MULTIPLE INHERITANCE (via Interfaces only):
Java does NOT allow a class to extend multiple classes. This restriction avoids the diamond problem — ambiguity when two parent classes define the same method. Multiple inheritance of type is achieved through interfaces.
interface Flyable { }
interface Drivable { }
class FlyingCar implements Flyable, Drivable { }

5. HYBRID INHERITANCE (via Interfaces):
A combination of inheritance types, achieved through interfaces.

Practical Example:
class Person {
    String name;
    void speak() { }
}

class Employee extends Person {  // Single inheritance
    double salary;
    void work() { }
}

class Manager extends Employee {  // Multilevel inheritance
    int teamSize;
    void manage() { }
}

// Hierarchical:
class Intern extends Employee { }  // Employee also has Intern

Key Rule: A class can extend only ONE class but can implement MULTIPLE interfaces.

Exception handling in Java is a mechanism that allows a program to handle runtime errors (exceptions) gracefully, preventing the program from crashing and providing meaningful error messages.

THE TRY-CATCH-FINALLY MECHANISM:

try {
    // Code that might throw an exception
    int result = 10 / 0;  // ArithmeticException
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    // Handle the specific exception
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero!");
} finally {
    // Always executes (even if return is called in try/catch)
    System.out.println("This always runs.");
}

HOW IT WORKS:
1. The try block contains code that may cause an exception
2. If an exception occurs, the JVM creates an exception object and looks for a matching catch block
3. The catch block executes if it handles the matching exception type
4. If no exception occurs, catch blocks are skipped
5. The finally block always executes — used for cleanup (closing files, database connections)

MULTIPLE CATCH BLOCKS:
try {
    String s = null;
    System.out.println(s.length());    // NullPointerException
    int[] arr = new int[5];
    arr[10] = 3;                       // ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
} catch (NullPointerException e) {
    System.out.println("Null reference!");
} catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    System.out.println("Array index out of bounds!");
} catch (Exception e) {
    // Generic catch block — should be last
    System.out.println("Some other exception: " + e);
}

CATCH-OR-DECLARE RULE:
- Checked exceptions must either be caught (try-catch) or declared (throws)
- Unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException) are optional to handle

Java 7+ allows multi-catch:
try {
    // code
} catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
    // handle both exception types the same way
}

CHECKED EXCEPTIONS:
- Checked at COMPILE TIME — the compiler verifies they are handled
- Must be caught with try-catch OR declared with throws in the method signature
- Extend the Exception class (but NOT RuntimeException)
- Represent external, recoverable errors (file not found, network failure, database error)
- Examples:
  - IOException (file read/write failures)
  - SQLException (database errors)
  - ClassNotFoundException (class not found on classpath)
  - InterruptedException (thread interruption)

Example of checked exception handling:
import java.io.*;

public void readFile(String path) {
    try {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);  // may throw FileNotFoundException
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);
        System.out.println(br.readLine());  // may throw IOException
    } catch (IOException e) {
        System.out.println("Error reading file: " + e.getMessage());
    }
}

// Alternatively, declare with throws:
public void readFile(String path) throws IOException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
    BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);
    System.out.println(br.readLine());
}

UNCHECKED EXCEPTIONS:
- NOT checked at compile time — the compiler does not enforce handling
- Extend RuntimeException
- Represent programming bugs (logic errors, null references, division by zero, array overflow)
- Can still be caught but are not required to be
- Examples:
  - NullPointerException (calling method on null)
  - ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException (index beyond array length)
  - ArithmeticException (division by zero)
  - IllegalArgumentException (invalid method argument)
  - NumberFormatException (invalid string-to-number conversion)

Example:
public void divide(int a, int b) {
    // No compile-time requirement to handle ArithmeticException
    int result = a / b;  // throws ArithmeticException if b == 0
}

KEY DIFFERENCE:
Checked exceptions force the programmer to handle potential failures at compile time. Unchecked exceptions indicate programming errors that should be fixed in code rather than caught at runtime.

THROW:
- Used to EXPLICITLY throw an exception object from within code
- Followed by an instance of Throwable (or its subclasses)
- Placed inside the method body
- Can only throw ONE exception at a time
- Stops the current execution and transfers control to the nearest catch block

Example:
public void checkAge(int age) {
    if (age < 18) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age must be 18 or older");
    }
    System.out.println("Access granted");
}

// Using throw with custom exception:
throw new ArithmeticException("Custom error message");

THROWS:
- Used in METHOD SIGNATURE to declare that the method may throw certain exceptions
- Followed by comma-separated exception class names
- Delegates the responsibility of handling exceptions to the caller
- Used primarily for checked exceptions
- The caller must catch or further declare these exceptions

Example:
public void readFile(String path) throws IOException, FileNotFoundException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);  // may throw FileNotFoundException
    BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);
    System.out.println(br.readLine());  // may throw IOException
}

// Caller must handle:
public void caller() {
    try {
        readFile("data.txt");
    } catch (IOException e) {
        System.out.println("File error: " + e.getMessage());
    }
}

KEY DIFFERENCES:
Feature        | throw                    | throws
---------------|--------------------------|--------------------------
Purpose        | Actually throw exception  | Declare possible exceptions
Location       | Inside method body        | Method signature
Keyword follows| Exception object          | Exception class name(s)
Quantity       | One at a time             | Multiple possible
Effect         | Stops execution           | Tells callers to handle

Both are commonly used together:
public void process(int value) throws IllegalArgumentException {
    if (value < 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Negative value not allowed");
    }
}

A custom exception in Java is a user-defined exception class created by extending either Exception (for checked exceptions) or RuntimeException (for unchecked exceptions).

STEPS TO CREATE A CUSTOM EXCEPTION:

1. EXTEND Exception or RuntimeException:
- Extend Exception for CHECKED custom exceptions (must be caught or declared)
- Extend RuntimeException for UNCHECKED custom exceptions (optional to handle)

2. Define a constructor that calls super(message):
- This passes the error message to the parent class

3. Optionally add extra fields and constructors:
- For more context about the error (e.g., error codes)

EXAMPLES:

// Checked custom exception
class InsufficientBalanceException extends Exception {
    private double deficit;

    public InsufficientBalanceException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }

    public InsufficientBalanceException(String message, double deficit) {
        super(message);
        this.deficit = deficit;
    }

    public double getDeficit() {
        return deficit;
    }
}

// Unchecked custom exception
class InvalidInputException extends RuntimeException {
    public InvalidInputException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

USING THE CUSTOM EXCEPTION:
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;

    public void withdraw(double amount) throws InsufficientBalanceException {
        if (amount > balance) {
            double deficit = amount - balance;
            throw new InsufficientBalanceException(
                "Insufficient balance. Short by $" + deficit, deficit);
        }
        balance -= amount;
    }

    public void process(String input) {
        if (input == null || input.isEmpty()) {
            throw new InvalidInputException("Input cannot be null or empty");
        }
    }
}

Caller handles the checked exception:
try {
    account.withdraw(500);
} catch (InsufficientBalanceException e) {
    System.out.println(e.getMessage());
    System.out.println("Deficit: $" + e.getDeficit());
}

Best practices:
- Name custom exceptions with 'Exception' suffix
- Document the exception with Javadoc
- Keep the exception specific to the error domain
- Provide constructors matching superclass patterns

The try-with-resources statement, introduced in Java 7, is a try statement that declares one or more resources (objects that implement AutoCloseable) and automatically closes them at the end of the statement. This simplifies resource management and reduces boilerplate code.

SYNTAX:
try (ResourceType resource = new ResourceType()) {
    // use resource
} catch (ExceptionType e) {
    // handle exception
}

EXAMPLE WITHOUT try-with-resources (old way):
BufferedReader br = null;
try {
    br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
    System.out.println(br.readLine());
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
} finally {
    if (br != null) {
        try {
            br.close();  // must close manually
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error closing: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

EXAMPLE WITH try-with-resources:
try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"))) {
    System.out.println(br.readLine());
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}
// br is automatically closed! No finally block needed.

MULTIPLE RESOURCES:
try (
    FileReader fr = new FileReader("input.txt");
    BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);
    PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter("output.txt")
) {
    String line = br.readLine();
    pw.println(line);
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}
// Resources are closed in reverse order: pw, br, fr

IMPORTANT POINTS:
1. Resources must implement AutoCloseable or Closeable interface
2. Available from Java 7 onwards
3. Resources are closed even if an exception occurs
4. Multiple resources are separated by semicolons
5. Can combine with regular try-catch and finally blocks (Java 9+ allows using effectively-final variables)
6. The compiler generates the close() calls automatically

Java 9 enhancement: Resources can be declared outside the try:
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
try (br) {  // br is effectively final
    System.out.println(br.readLine());
}

Static members (variables, methods, blocks) belong to the CLASS rather than to any specific object/instance of the class. They are shared by all objects of the class and can be accessed using the class name without creating an object.

1. STATIC VARIABLES (Class Variables):
Shared by all instances. Only one copy exists regardless of how many objects are created.

class Employee {
    String name;             // instance variable
    static String company;   // static variable — shared by all employees
    static int count = 0;    // static variable — tracks total employees

    Employee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        count++;  // increments for every new employee
    }
}

// All employees share the same 'company' value
Employee e1 = new Employee("Alice");
Employee e2 = new Employee("Bob");
Employee.company = "TechCorp";  // set once, affects all
System.out.println(e1.count);   // 2 — shared count

2. STATIC METHODS (Class Methods):
Can be called without creating an object. They cannot directly access instance variables (only static members).

class MathUtils {
    static int square(int x) {
        return x * x;
    }

    static double circleArea(double radius) {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;  // Math.PI is also static
    }
}

int result = MathUtils.square(5);  // called without object

3. STATIC BLOCKS:
Code that runs once when the class is first loaded into memory. Used for static initialization.

class Database {
    static Connection conn;

    static {
        // Runs once when Database class is loaded
        conn = DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:mysql://localhost/db");
        System.out.println("Database connected");
    }
}

KEY RULES:
- Static methods can only call other static methods directly
- Static methods can only access static variables directly
- Static methods cannot use 'this' or 'super'
- Instance methods can access both static and instance members
- Access static members via ClassName.member (best practice), though object.member also works (not recommended)

Java's Math class is entirely static — all its methods and constants (PI, E) are static.

Composition is an OOP design principle where a class contains an object of another class as a field, representing a HAS-A relationship. The contained object's lifecycle is tied to the container — when the container is destroyed, the contained object is also destroyed.

COMPOSITION vs INHERITANCE:

COMPOSITION (HAS-A):
class Engine {
    void start() { System.out.println("Engine started"); }
}

class Car {
    private Engine engine;  // Car HAS-A Engine

    Car() {
        engine = new Engine();  // Engine created with Car
    }

    void start() {
        engine.start();  // delegating to Engine
    }
}
// Car contains Engine. If Car is destroyed, Engine is also gone.

INHERITANCE (IS-A):
class Vehicle {
    void move() { }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {  // Car IS-A Vehicle
    // inherits move()
}

KEY DIFFERENCES:

1. RELATIONSHIP:
- Composition: HAS-A (Car has an Engine)
- Inheritance: IS-A (Car is a Vehicle)

2. KEYWORD:
- Composition: Uses object references (fields)
- Inheritance: Uses the extends keyword

3. FLEXIBILITY:
- Composition: More flexible — can change behavior at runtime by swapping components
- Inheritance: Fixed at compile time — the parent-child relationship cannot change

4. COUPLING:
- Composition: Looser coupling — classes are independent
- Inheritance: Tighter coupling — child depends on parent's implementation

5. CODE REUSE:
- Composition: Reuses functionality by delegating to contained objects
- Inheritance: Reuses functionality by inheriting methods from parent

6. ENCAPSULATION:
- Composition: Better — internal components are hidden
- Inheritance: Weaker — child can access parent's protected members

DESIGN PRINCIPLE:
"Favor composition over inheritance" — Use composition when the relationship is 'has-a' and when you want flexibility. Use inheritance when the relationship is truly 'is-a' and the subclass will not need to change the parent's behavior.

AGGREGATION (weaker form of composition):
class Department {
    List<Employee> employees;  // Department HAS-A Employee
    // But Employee can exist without Department (lifecycle independent)
}

The Student Directory is a classic OOP case study that demonstrates separation of concerns in Java. The application manages student records with the following classes:

1. STUDENT CLASS (Model):
Represents a single student entity with fields like name, ID number, course, etc.
public class Student {
    private String name;
    private int id;
    private String course;

    // Constructor, getters, setters
    public Student(String name, int id, String course) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
        this.course = course;
    }

    // display() method to show student details
}

2. STUDENTDATABASE CLASS (Data Layer):
Manages the collection of Student objects. Handles adding, removing, searching, and listing students.
public class StudentDatabase {
    private ArrayList<Student> students;  // in-memory storage

    public void addStudent(Student s) { ... }
    public Student findById(int id) { ... }
    public void removeStudent(int id) { ... }
    public ArrayList<Student> getAllStudents() { ... }
}

3. KEYBOARD CLASS (Input Handler):
Handles all user input from the console. Provides methods to read specific data types.
public class Keyboard {
    public static int readInt() { ... }
    public static String readString() { ... }
    // Reads input from System.in with error handling
}

4. OUTPUT CLASS (Output Handler):
Manages all display/output to the console.
public class Output {
    public static void displayMenu() { ... }
    public static void displayStudent(Student s) { ... }
    public static void displayAllStudents(ArrayList<Student> list) { ... }
    public static void displayMessage(String msg) { ... }
}

5. STUDENTDIRECTORY CLASS (Controller):
The main controller that ties everything together. Contains the main menu loop.
public class StudentDirectory {
    private StudentDatabase database;

    public void run() {
        // Main menu loop
        int choice;
        do {
            Output.displayMenu();
            choice = Keyboard.readInt();
            switch(choice) {
                case 1: addStudent(); break;
                case 2: listStudents(); break;
                case 3: searchStudent(); break;
                case 4: removeStudent(); break;
                case 5: System.out.println("Goodbye!"); break;
            }
        } while (choice != 5);
    }
}

DESIGN PRINCIPLES DEMONSTRATED:
- Separation of Concerns: Each class has a single, well-defined responsibility
- Modularity: Classes can be developed, tested, and maintained independently
- Reusability: Keyboard, Output classes can be reused in other console applications
- Encapsulation: Data is hidden behind methods
- Main method in a separate driver class creates the StudentDirectory and calls run()

Swing is Java's primary GUI (Graphical User Interface) framework, part of the javax.swing package. It provides a rich set of platform-independent components for building desktop applications.

JFRAME:
- The main window of a Swing application
- Has a title bar, minimize/maximize/close buttons
- Can be resized by default
- Has a content pane where components are added
- Created by extending JFrame or instantiating it directly

JFrame example:
import javax.swing.*;

public class MainWindow extends JFrame {
    public MainWindow() {
        setTitle("My Application");  // window title
        setSize(500, 400);           // width, height in pixels
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);  // exit on close
        setLocationRelativeTo(null); // center on screen
        setVisible(true);            // make the window visible
    }
}

// Or using JFrame directly:
JFrame frame = new JFrame("My App");
frame.setSize(500, 400);
frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
frame.setVisible(true);

JPANEL:
- A lightweight container used to GROUP and ORGANIZE components
- Can hold buttons, labels, text fields, and other components
- Can have its own layout manager
- Usually added to the JFrame's content pane
- Multiple JPanels can be layered for complex layouts

JPanel example:
JPanel panel = new JPanel();  // default layout is FlowLayout
panel.add(new JButton("Click Me"));
panel.add(new JLabel("Welcome!"));
panel.add(new JTextField(20));

JFrame frame = new JFrame("My App");
frame.add(panel);  // adds panel to content pane

WORKING TOGETHER:
JFrame frame = new JFrame("Student Directory");
frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
frame.setSize(600, 400);

JPanel inputPanel = new JPanel();
inputPanel.add(new JLabel("Name:"));
inputPanel.add(new JTextField(20));
inputPanel.add(new JButton("Add"));

JPanel listPanel = new JPanel();
listPanel.add(new JScrollPane(new JTextArea(10, 40)));

frame.add(inputPanel, BorderLayout.NORTH);
frame.add(listPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

frame.setVisible(true);

KEY POINTS:
- JFrame is the top-level window; JPanel is a nested container
- You should add components to JPanel, then add JPanel to JFrame
- JFrame's setVisible(true) must be called last to show the GUI
- JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE terminates the program when the window closes

Java Swing uses the delegation event model for event handling. In this model:
- Event SOURCE generates events (e.g., JButton when clicked)
- Event LISTENER registers with the source to receive notifications
- When an event occurs, the source calls the appropriate listener method

THE ACTIONLISTENER INTERFACE:
ActionListener is in the java.awt.event package and has a SINGLE method:

public interface ActionListener {
    void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e);
}

IMPLEMENTING EVENT HANDLING (three ways):

1. IMPLEMENTING ACTIONLISTENER IN THE CLASS:
public class MyFrame extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton btn = new JButton("Click");

    MyFrame() {
        btn.addActionListener(this);  // register
        add(btn);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        System.out.println("Button clicked!");
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Hello!");
    }
}

2. USING AN ANONYMOUS INNER CLASS:
JButton btn = new JButton("Click");
btn.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        System.out.println("Button clicked!");
    }
});

3. USING LAMBDA EXPRESSION (Java 8+):
JButton btn = new JButton("Click");
btn.addActionListener(e -> System.out.println("Button clicked!"));

THE ACTIONEVENT OBJECT:
The actionPerformed method receives an ActionEvent that provides information:
- getSource(): returns the component that fired the event
- getActionCommand(): returns the action command string (default: button text)
- getModifiers(): returns modifier keys held during the event

Common components that fire action events:
- JButton (when clicked)
- JTextField (when Enter is pressed)
- JMenuItem (when selected)
- JCheckBox, JRadioButton (when toggled)

Example with multiple buttons:
JButton addBtn = new JButton("Add");
JButton clearBtn = new JButton("Clear");

ActionListener listener = e -> {
    String cmd = e.getActionCommand();
    switch (cmd) {
        case "Add":   // perform add logic
        case "Clear": // perform clear logic
    }
};

addBtn.addActionListener(listener);
clearBtn.addActionListener(listener);

Common Swing components include JLabel, JTextField, JButton, JTextArea, JCheckBox, JRadioButton, JComboBox, JList, JTable, and JScrollPane. Here are three fundamental components:

1. JLABEL:
Displays read-only text or an image. Cannot be edited by the user.

JLabel label = new JLabel("Enter your name:");
JLabel imageLabel = new JLabel(new ImageIcon("icon.png"));
label.setText("Updated text");     // change the text
String text = label.getText();      // get the text
label.setHorizontalAlignment(SwingConstants.CENTER);

2. JTEXTFIELD:
Allows the user to enter a single line of text.

JTextField textField = new JTextField(20);         // 20 columns wide
JTextField textField2 = new JTextField("Default"); // with initial text
String input = textField.getText();                // get entered text
textField.setText("");                             // clear the field
textField.setEditable(false);                      // make read-only

3. JBUTTON:
Triggers an action when clicked by the user.

JButton btn = new JButton("Submit");
btn.setEnabled(false);              // disable the button
btn.setText("Click Here");         // change button text
btn.addActionListener(e -> {
    System.out.println("Button clicked!");
});

PUTTING THEM TOGETHER (simple form):
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class SimpleForm {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Simple Form");
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setSize(400, 150);

        JPanel panel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());
        JLabel label = new JLabel("Name:");
        JTextField textField = new JTextField(15);
        JButton submitBtn = new JButton("Submit");
        JLabel resultLabel = new JLabel("");

        submitBtn.addActionListener(e -> {
            String name = textField.getText();
            resultLabel.setText("Hello, " + name + "!");
        });

        panel.add(label);
        panel.add(textField);
        panel.add(submitBtn);
        panel.add(resultLabel);

        frame.add(panel);
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}

OTHER COMMON COMPONENTS:
- JTextArea: Multi-line text input
- JCheckBox: Checkbox (boolean option)
- JRadioButton: Radio button (grouped with ButtonGroup)
- JComboBox: Drop-down list
- JList: List selection
- JScrollPane: Adds scroll bars to another component
- JPasswordField: For password input (hides characters)
- JOptionPane: For dialog boxes (input, confirmation, message)

Layout managers in Swing automatically control the positioning and sizing of components within a container. They adapt to different window sizes and platform differences.

1. FLOWLAYOUT:
- Default layout for JPanel
- Components are placed left-to-right in a row, wrapping to a new row when needed
- Each component gets its preferred size
- Uses: simple sequential layouts, toolbars

JPanel panel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());  // default
JPanel panel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.LEFT, 10, 20));
// alignment, hgap, vgap

panel.add(new JButton("A"));
panel.add(new JButton("B"));
panel.add(new JButton("C"));
// Result: [A] [B] [C] in a row

2. BORDERLAYOUT:
- Default layout for JFrame's content pane
- Divides container into 5 regions: NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, WEST, CENTER
- Each region can hold at most one component
- NORTH/SOUTH: component gets preferred height, full width
- EAST/WEST: component gets preferred width, remaining height
- CENTER: gets all remaining space
- Uses: main application windows

JFrame frame = new JFrame();
frame.setLayout(new BorderLayout());

frame.add(new JButton("Top"), BorderLayout.NORTH);
frame.add(new JButton("Bottom"), BorderLayout.SOUTH);
frame.add(new JButton("Left"), BorderLayout.WEST);
frame.add(new JButton("Right"), BorderLayout.EAST);
frame.add(new JTextArea(), BorderLayout.CENTER);  // gets remaining space

3. GRIDLAYOUT:
- Divides container into equal-sized cells in a grid
- All cells have the same size
- Components fill their entire cell
- When the window resizes, all cells resize equally
- Uses: calculator buttons, form layouts

JPanel panel = new JPanel(new GridLayout(3, 2));  // 3 rows, 2 columns
// or: new GridLayout(3, 2, 5, 5) with hgap=5, vgap=5

panel.add(new JLabel("Name:"));
panel.add(new JTextField());
panel.add(new JLabel("Age:"));
panel.add(new JTextField());
panel.add(new JLabel("Email:"));
panel.add(new JTextField());
// Creates a 3x2 grid of label-field pairs

OTHER LAYOUT MANAGERS:
- CardLayout: stacks components like cards, showing one at a time
- GridBagLayout: most flexible but complex — components can span multiple cells
- BoxLayout: arranges components in single row or column
- GroupLayout: NetBeans-generated layouts (used by GUI builder)

COMBINING LAYOUTS:
JFrame (BorderLayout)
  +-- JPanel (FlowLayout)   -- NORTH (toolbar)
  +-- JPanel (GridLayout)   -- CENTER (form)
  +-- JPanel (FlowLayout)   -- SOUTH (status bar)

Example:
JFrame frame = new JFrame("Student Directory");
JPanel centerPanel = new JPanel(new GridLayout(4, 2));
centerPanel.add(new JLabel("Name:"));
centerPanel.add(new JTextField());
centerPanel.add(new JLabel("ID:"));
centerPanel.add(new JTextField());

JPanel buttonPanel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());
buttonPanel.add(new JButton("Add"));
buttonPanel.add(new JButton("Clear"));

frame.add(centerPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);
frame.add(buttonPanel, BorderLayout.SOUTH);

The key difference between these two pairs is that FileReader/FileWriter operate on CHARACTERS (text) while FileInputStream/FileOutputStream operate on BYTES (binary data).

CHARACTER STREAMS (FileReader / FileWriter):
- Work with characters (text)
- Automatically handle character encoding (UTF-8, etc.)
- Extend abstract classes Reader and Writer
- Best for reading/writing text files (.txt, .csv, .html, .java)
- Often wrapped with BufferedReader/BufferedWriter for efficiency

FILEWRITER example:
FileWriter writer = new FileWriter("output.txt");
writer.write("Hello, World!");
writer.write("\nNew line of text");
writer.close();  // always close

FILEREADER example:
FileReader reader = new FileReader("input.txt");
int ch;
while ((ch = reader.read()) != -1) {
    System.out.print((char) ch);  // reads one character at a time
}
reader.close();

With BufferedReader (more efficient):
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"));
String line;
while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
br.close();

BYTE STREAMS (FileInputStream / FileOutputStream):
- Work with raw bytes (binary data)
- No character encoding — reads/writes bytes as-is
- Extend abstract classes InputStream and OutputStream
- Best for binary files (images, audio, video, PDF, ZIP)
- Suitable for copying files regardless of type

FILEOUTPUTSTREAM example:
FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("image_copy.jpg");
byte[] imageData = ... ;  // binary data
fos.write(imageData);
fos.close();

FILEINPUTSTREAM example:
FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("image.jpg");
int byteRead;
while ((byteRead = fis.read()) != -1) {
    // process byte
}
fis.close();

With BufferedInputStream (more efficient):
BufferedInputStream bis = new BufferedInputStream(new FileInputStream("large.mp4"));
byte[] buffer = new byte[4096];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = bis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
    // process buffer
}
bis.close();

SUMMARY:
Feature        | FileReader/Writer     | FileInputStream/OutputStream
---------------|-----------------------|-------------------------------
Data type      | Characters (text)     | Bytes (binary)
File types     | .txt, .csv, .java     | .jpg, .mp4, .pdf, .zip
Encoding       | Auto-handled          | Raw bytes, no encoding
Parent class   | Reader/Writer         | InputStream/OutputStream
Wrapping       | BufferedReader/Writer | BufferedInputStream/OutputStream
Best for       | Text processing       | Binary file copying/manipulation

Scanner and PrintWriter are convenient classes for reading from and writing to text files in Java.

READING WITH SCANNER:
Scanner provides nextLine(), nextInt(), nextDouble(), etc. for parsing text files.

import java.io.*;
import java.util.Scanner;

public void readFile(String path) {
    try (Scanner scanner = new Scanner(new File(path))) {
        while (scanner.hasNextLine()) {
            String line = scanner.nextLine();
            System.out.println(line);
        }
    } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
        System.out.println("File not found: " + path);
    }
}

Reading structured data (CSV):
try (Scanner sc = new Scanner(new File("students.csv"))) {
    while (sc.hasNextLine()) {
        String line = sc.nextLine();
        String[] parts = line.split(",");
        String name = parts[0];
        int id = Integer.parseInt(parts[1]);
        String course = parts[2];
        System.out.println(name + " - " + id + " - " + course);
    }
}

Reading numbers:
try (Scanner sc = new Scanner(new File("numbers.txt"))) {
    int sum = 0;
    while (sc.hasNextInt()) {
        sum += sc.nextInt();
    }
    System.out.println("Sum: " + sum);
}

WRITING WITH PRINTWRITER:
PrintWriter provides println(), printf(), and print() for formatted text output.

public void writeFile(String path) {
    try (PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(new File(path))) {
        pw.println("Student Report");
        pw.println("=============");
        pw.printf("Name: %s, ID: %d%n", "Alice", 101);
        pw.printf("Name: %s, ID: %d%n", "Bob", 102);
        pw.println("Total students: 2");
    } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
        System.out.println("Error writing file: " + e.getMessage());
    }
}

Using FileWriter with PrintWriter (for append mode or encoding):
PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter("log.txt", true));  // true = append
pw.println("New log entry");

COMPLETE EXAMPLE (copy character by character):
public void copyFile(String source, String dest) {
    try (
        Scanner reader = new Scanner(new File(source));
        PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(new File(dest))
    ) {
        while (reader.hasNextLine()) {
            writer.println(reader.nextLine());
        }
        System.out.println("File copied successfully.");
    } catch (IOException e) {
        System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
    }
}

KEY METHODS:
Scanner:          | PrintWriter:
- hasNextLine()   | - println(String)
- nextLine()      | - print(String)
- hasNextInt()    | - printf(format, args...)
- nextInt()       | - format(format, args...)
- useDelimiter()  | - flush()
- close()         | - close()

Both are typically used with try-with-resources (Java 7+) for automatic closing.

Serialization in Java is the process of converting an object's state into a byte stream that can be saved to a file, sent over a network, or stored in a database. Deserialization is the reverse process — reconstructing the object from the byte stream.

HOW TO MAKE A CLASS SERIALIZABLE:
A class must implement the Serializable marker interface (an interface with no methods).

import java.io.*;

class Student implements Serializable {
    private String name;
    private int id;
    private String course;
    private transient double gpa;    // will NOT be serialized
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;  // version control

    public Student(String name, int id, String course) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
        this.course = course;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return name + " (" + id + ") - " + course;
    }
}

SERIALIZING AN OBJECT (ObjectOutputStream):
public void serializeStudent(Student s, String filePath) {
    try (ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(
            new FileOutputStream(filePath))) {
        oos.writeObject(s);
        System.out.println("Object serialized to " + filePath);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        System.out.println("Serialization error: " + e.getMessage());
    }
}

DESERIALIZING AN OBJECT (ObjectInputStream):
public Student deserializeStudent(String filePath) {
    try (ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(
            new FileInputStream(filePath))) {
        Student s = (Student) ois.readObject();  // cast required
        return s;
    } catch (IOException | ClassNotFoundException e) {
        System.out.println("Deserialization error: " + e.getMessage());
        return null;
    }
}

USAGE:
Student s1 = new Student("Alice", 101, "CSC 282");
serializeStudent(s1, "student.ser");  // save to file

Student restored = deserializeStudent("student.ser");
System.out.println(restored);  // Alice (101) - CSC 282

KEY CONCEPTS:

1. serialVersionUID:
- A unique identifier for each serializable class
- Used during deserialization to verify the sender and receiver have compatible classes
- If not declared, Java generates one automatically (but can vary between compilers)
- Always declare explicitly: private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

2. TRANSIENT KEYWORD:
- Fields marked transient are NOT serialized
- Used for sensitive data (passwords) or derived data (calculated values)
- On deserialization, transient fields get default values (null for objects, 0 for numbers)

3. STATIC FIELDS:
- Static fields belong to the class, not the object
- They are NOT serialized (they are loaded as part of the class definition)

4. WHEN IS SERIALIZATION USED?
- Saving application state to files
- Sending objects over network sockets
- Distributed systems (RMI — Remote Method Invocation)
- Session replication in web servers
- Caching objects to disk

5. CUSTOM SERIALIZATION:
Classes can override writeObject() and readObject() for custom serialization logic.

JDBC (Java Database Connectivity) is an API that enables Java applications to interact with relational databases. It provides methods for connecting to a database, executing SQL queries, and processing results.

STEPS TO CONNECT TO A DATABASE:

STEP 1: LOAD THE JDBC DRIVER (optional in JDBC 4.0+):
// In older JDBC, needed to load the driver class
// Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");
// In JDBC 4.0+, the driver is auto-loaded if on classpath

STEP 2: ESTABLISH A CONNECTION:
String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb";
String user = "root";
String password = "password";

Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, password);

Different database URLs:
- MySQL:    jdbc:mysql://host:port/database
- PostgreSQL: jdbc:postgresql://host:port/database
- Oracle:   jdbc:oracle:thin:@host:port:database
- SQLite:   jdbc:sqlite:database.db

STEP 3: CREATE A STATEMENT:
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
// OR (preferred):
PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement("SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = ?");

STEP 4: EXECUTE SQL AND PROCESS RESULTS:
// For SELECT queries:
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students");
while (rs.next()) {
    int id = rs.getInt("id");
    String name = rs.getString("name");
    String course = rs.getString("course");
    System.out.println(id + " - " + name + " - " + course);
}

// For INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE:
int rows = stmt.executeUpdate("INSERT INTO students VALUES(101, 'Alice', 'CSC 282')");

STEP 5: CLOSE RESOURCES:
rs.close();
stmt.close();
conn.close();

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
import java.sql.*;

public class DatabaseDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb";

        try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, "root", "password");
             Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
             ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students")) {

            while (rs.next()) {
                System.out.println(rs.getString("name"));
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            System.out.println("Database error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        // Resources are auto-closed by try-with-resources
    }
}

TIPS:
- Always use try-with-resources for automatic cleanup
- Use PreparedStatement instead of Statement (prevents SQL injection)
- The JDBC driver JAR must be on the classpath
- Connection parameters can be stored in configuration files

Statement and PreparedStatement are both used to execute SQL queries in JDBC, but they differ significantly in security, performance, and usability.

1. PREVENTION OF SQL INJECTION (Most Important):

Statement (vulnerable):
String userInput = "1 OR 1=1";
String sql = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = " + userInput;
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(sql);
// Executes: SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = 1 OR 1=1  -- RETURNS ALL ROWS!

PreparedStatement (safe):
String sql = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = ?";
PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql);
pstmt.setInt(1, Integer.parseInt(userInput));  // input is treated as data, not SQL
ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery();
// Even if userInput = "1 OR 1=1", setInt will throw NumberFormatException

2. PERFORMANCE:

Statement: SQL is compiled every time it is executed.

PreparedStatement: SQL is precompiled once and reused. For batch operations, this is significantly faster.

// Batch insert using PreparedStatement
PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement("INSERT INTO students VALUES(?, ?, ?)");
for (Student s : students) {
    pstmt.setInt(1, s.getId());
    pstmt.setString(2, s.getName());
    pstmt.setString(3, s.getCourse());
    pstmt.addBatch();  // add to batch
}
pstmt.executeBatch();  // execute all at once

3. READABILITY AND MAINTAINABILITY:

Statement (harder to read):
String sql = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE course = '" + course + "' AND year = " + year;

PreparedStatement (cleaner):
String sql = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE course = ? AND year = ?";
PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql);
pstmt.setString(1, course);
pstmt.setInt(2, year);

4. DATA TYPE HANDLING:
PreparedStatement provides type-specific setter methods:
- setInt(int index, int value)
- setString(int index, String value)
- setDouble(int index, double value)
- setDate(int index, Date value)
- setObject(int index, Object value)

5. AUTO-GENERATED KEYS:
Both can retrieve auto-generated keys:

PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql, Statement.RETURN_GENERATED_KEYS);
ResultSet rs = pstmt.getGeneratedKeys();

SUMMARY:
Feature          | Statement               | PreparedStatement
-----------------|-------------------------|--------------------------
SQL Injection    | Vulnerable              | Protected
Performance      | Compiled each time      | Precompiled, reusable
Parameters       | String concatenation    | ? placeholders
Readability      | Poor (string concat)    | Clean
Batch processing | Manual                  | Built-in addBatch()
Type casting     | Manual conversion       | Automatic (setInt, etc.)
Use case         | Dynamic SQL/DDL queries | Parameterized queries

ALWAYS use PreparedStatement when accepting user input or executing the same query multiple times.

ResultSet is an interface in JDBC that represents the result set of a SQL query. It contains the rows returned by the database and provides methods to navigate through and retrieve data from those rows.

CURSOR NAVIGATION:
A ResultSet maintains a cursor (pointer) to the current row. Initially, the cursor is positioned BEFORE the first row.

- next(): Moves the cursor to the next row. Returns true if a valid row exists, false if no more rows.
- previous(): Moves the cursor backward (requires scrollable ResultSet)
- first() / last(): Move to first/last row (requires scrollable ResultSet)
- absolute(int row): Move to a specific row (requires scrollable ResultSet)
- beforeFirst() / afterLast(): Move to before first / after last row

FORWARD-ONLY (default):
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students");

while (rs.next()) {  // moves forward one row
    // process current row
}

SCROLLABLE ResultSet:
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement(
    ResultSet.TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,  // or TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE
    ResultSet.CONCUR_READ_ONLY
);
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students");

rs.last();
int rowCount = rs.getRow();  // get current row number (total rows)

rs.first();
String firstName = rs.getString("name");

rs.absolute(3);  // go to row 3

RETRIEVING DATA:
Data is retrieved using getter methods, either by column INDEX (1-based) or column NAME.

ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT id, name, course FROM students");

while (rs.next()) {
    // By column index (1-based: first column = 1):
    int id = rs.getInt(1);
    String name = rs.getString(2);

    // By column name (more readable):
    String course = rs.getString("course");

    System.out.println(id + " - " + name + " - " + course);
}

COMMON GETTER METHODS:
- getInt(int/string): retrieves an integer
- getString(int/string): retrieves a String
- getDouble(int/string): retrieves a double
- getBoolean(int/string): retrieves a boolean
- getDate(int/string): retrieves a java.sql.Date
- getTimestamp(int/string): retrieves a Timestamp
- getObject(int/string): retrieves an Object (generic)
- getBlob(int/string): retrieves a Blob (binary large object)

HANDLING NULL VALUES:
ResultSet methods return 0 or false for SQL NULL by default. Use wasNull() to check:

int value = rs.getInt("score");
if (rs.wasNull()) {
    // value was NULL in database, but returned 0
    value = -1;  // handle appropriately
}

UPDATING DATA THROUGH ResultSet (updateable ResultSet):
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement(
    ResultSet.TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY,
    ResultSet.CONCUR_UPDATABLE
);
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT id, name FROM students");

rs.next();
rs.updateString("name", "New Name");
rs.updateRow();  // save changes to database

ALWAYS close ResultSet after use (try-with-resources handles this automatically):
try (Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
     ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students")) {
    while (rs.next()) {
        // process
    }
}

Connection pooling is a technique where a pool of database connections is created and maintained, ready to be reused by multiple clients. Instead of creating a new connection for every database operation (which is expensive), applications borrow a connection from the pool, use it, and return it to the pool.

WHY IS CONNECTION CREATION EXPENSIVE?
Establishing a database connection involves:
1. TCP/IP network handshake
2. Authentication (username/password verification)
3. Database session initialization
4. Memory allocation on both client and server
This can take 100-500ms per connection — very costly for web applications handling many requests.

WITHOUT CONNECTION POOLING:
// Every request creates a new connection
public void processRequest() {
    Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);  // expensive!
    // do database work
    conn.close();  // connection is destroyed
}
// 1000 requests = 1000 connections created and destroyed

WITH CONNECTION POOLING (using HikariCP):
HikariConfig config = new HikariConfig();
config.setJdbcUrl("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb");
config.setUsername("root");
config.setPassword("password");
config.setMaximumPoolSize(10);  // max 10 connections

HikariDataSource dataSource = new HikariDataSource(config);

// Every request borrows and returns a connection:
public void processRequest() {
    try (Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection()) {  // fast! borrowed from pool
        // do database work
    }  // connection is returned to pool, not closed
}

BENEFITS OF CONNECTION POOLING:

1. PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENT:
- Borrowing a connection from the pool takes microseconds
- Creating a new connection takes hundreds of milliseconds
- Significant latency reduction for each database operation

2. RESOURCE MANAGEMENT:
- Limits the total number of connections to the database
- Prevents connection leak exhaustion
- Database servers have a max connection limit (e.g., MySQL default: 151)
- Without pooling, each request could exhaust available connections

3. CONNECTION HEALTH:
- Pools validate connections before handing them out
- Stale/broken connections are automatically detected and replaced
- Idle connections can be closed to free resources

4. CONFIGURATION OPTIONS (HikariCP):
- maximumPoolSize: max connections in pool
- minimumIdle: min idle connections to maintain
- connectionTimeout: max wait time for a connection
- idleTimeout: max time a connection can be idle
- maxLifetime: max lifetime of a connection in the pool
- validationTimeout: timeout for connection validation

EXAMPLE CONFIGURATION:
HikariConfig config = new HikariConfig();
config.setJdbcUrl("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb");
config.setUsername("root");
config.setPassword("password");
config.setMaximumPoolSize(20);
config.setMinimumIdle(5);
config.setConnectionTimeout(30000);     // 30 seconds
config.setIdleTimeout(600000);          // 10 minutes
config.setMaxLifetime(1800000);         // 30 minutes

HikariDataSource dataSource = new HikariDataSource(config);

// Use in application
Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection();
// ... use connection ...
conn.close();  // returns to pool

Enterprise Java uses javax.sql.DataSource:
DataSource ds = (DataSource) new InitialContext().lookup("jdbc/studentDS");
Connection conn = ds.getConnection();  // pooled connection

CRUD stands for Create, Read, Update, Delete — the four basic operations for persistent data storage. Here's how to implement each using JDBC PreparedStatement:

C — CREATE (INSERT):
public void addStudent(Student s) throws SQLException {
    String sql = "INSERT INTO students (id, name, course, gpa) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?)";

    try (Connection conn = getConnection();
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {

        pstmt.setInt(1, s.getId());
        pstmt.setString(2, s.getName());
        pstmt.setString(3, s.getCourse());
        pstmt.setDouble(4, s.getGpa());

        int rowsInserted = pstmt.executeUpdate();
        System.out.println(rowsInserted + " student(s) added.");
    }
}

R — READ (SELECT):
public Student getStudentById(int id) throws SQLException {
    String sql = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = ?";

    try (Connection conn = getConnection();
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {

        pstmt.setInt(1, id);

        try (ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {
            if (rs.next()) {
                return new Student(
                    rs.getInt("id"),
                    rs.getString("name"),
                    rs.getString("course"),
                    rs.getDouble("gpa")
                );
            }
        }
    }
    return null;
}

// READ all:
public List<Student> getAllStudents() throws SQLException {
    List<Student> students = new ArrayList<>();
    String sql = "SELECT * FROM students";

    try (Connection conn = getConnection();
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql);
         ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {

        while (rs.next()) {
            students.add(new Student(
                rs.getInt("id"),
                rs.getString("name"),
                rs.getString("course"),
                rs.getDouble("gpa")
            ));
        }
    }
    return students;
}

U — UPDATE:
public boolean updateStudentCourse(int id, String newCourse) throws SQLException {
    String sql = "UPDATE students SET course = ? WHERE id = ?";

    try (Connection conn = getConnection();
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {

        pstmt.setString(1, newCourse);
        pstmt.setInt(2, id);

        int rowsUpdated = pstmt.executeUpdate();
        return rowsUpdated > 0;
    }
}

D — DELETE:
public boolean deleteStudent(int id) throws SQLException {
    String sql = "DELETE FROM students WHERE id = ?";

    try (Connection conn = getConnection();
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {

        pstmt.setInt(1, id);

        int rowsDeleted = pstmt.executeUpdate();
        return rowsDeleted > 0;
    }
}

COMPLETE DAO (Data Access Object) PATTERN:
public class StudentDAO {
    private static final String INSERT_SQL = "INSERT INTO students VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?)";
    private static final String SELECT_BY_ID_SQL = "SELECT * FROM students WHERE id = ?";
    private static final String SELECT_ALL_SQL = "SELECT * FROM students";
    private static final String UPDATE_SQL = "UPDATE students SET name=?, course=?, gpa=? WHERE id=?";
    private static final String DELETE_SQL = "DELETE FROM students WHERE id = ?";

    private Connection getConnection() throws SQLException {
        // from connection pool
        return dataSource.getConnection();
    }

    // CRUD methods go here
}

PRACTICE TIPS:
- Always use try-with-resources to ensure resources are closed
- Keep SQL strings as constants (static final)
- Use the DAO pattern to separate data access from business logic
- Use connection pooling (HikariCP) in production

Dynamic method dispatch is the mechanism in Java by which a call to an overridden method is resolved at runtime rather than at compile time. The JVM determines which version of the method to execute based on the actual type of the object, not the type of the reference variable.

HOW IT WORKS:
When a method is called on a reference variable, the JVM:
1. Looks at the actual object type (the type created with new)
2. Checks if that type has an overridden version of the method
3. If yes, calls the overridden version
4. If no, walks up the inheritance hierarchy

EXAMPLE:
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Cat meows");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a;  // reference variable of type Animal

        a = new Animal();
        a.sound();  // "Animal makes a sound"

        a = new Dog();   // upcasting — Dog object assigned to Animal reference
        a.sound();  // "Dog barks"  (dynamic dispatch!)

        a = new Cat();   // upcasting — Cat object assigned to Animal reference
        a.sound();  // "Cat meows"  (dynamic dispatch!)

        // The SAME reference 'a' calls DIFFERENT methods
        // based on what object type it points to at runtime
    }
}

KEY POINTS:

1. UPCASTING: A parent reference can hold a child object. This is always safe and does not require explicit casting.
   Animal a = new Dog();  // upcasting (implicit)

2. DOWNCASTING: Converting parent reference back to child type. Requires explicit casting and can throw ClassCastException.
   Dog d = (Dog) a;  // downcasting (explicit)

3. METHOD CALL RESOLUTION:
   - For non-static methods: resolved at runtime (dynamic dispatch)
   - For static methods: resolved at compile time (no polymorphism)
   - For fields: resolved at compile time (no polymorphism)

4. PRACTICAL BENEFIT:
   - Write code that works with the parent type, and it automatically works with any new subclass
   - New subclasses can be added without changing existing code (Open/Closed Principle)

EXAMPLE OF EXTENSIBILITY:
public static void makeSound(Animal a) {
    a.sound();  // works for ANY Animal subclass
}

makeSound(new Dog());  // "Dog barks"
makeSound(new Cat());  // "Cat meows"
makeSound(new Cow());  // if we add Cow class — no code change needed!

This is the foundation of polymorphic behavior in Java.

Covariant return type, introduced in Java 5, allows an overriding method in a subclass to return a more specific (subtype) return type than the method it overrides in the parent class.

BEFORE JAVA 5 (exact match required):
class Parent {
    Object getValue() { return new Object(); }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    Object getValue() { return "Hello"; }  // had to return Object, even though String is a subclass
}

// Usage required casting:
String s = (String) new Child().getValue();  // explicit cast needed

WITH COVARIANT RETURN TYPE (Java 5+):
class Parent {
    Object getValue() { return new Object(); }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    String getValue() { return "Hello"; }  // String is a subtype of Object — allowed!
}

// Usage — no cast needed:
String s = new Child().getValue();  // automatic!

ANOTHER EXAMPLE:
class Animal {
    Animal reproduce() { return new Animal(); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    Dog reproduce() { return new Dog(); }  // Dog is covariant return type (subtype of Animal)
}

// Usage:
Dog puppy = new Dog().reproduce();  // no cast needed

RULES:
1. The overriding method's return type must be a subtype of the overridden method's return type
2. Works with reference types (classes, interfaces) — not with primitives
3. The subtype relationship must hold through the inheritance chain
4. Eliminates unnecessary downcasting, making code cleaner and type-safe

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
class Shape {
    Shape clone() { return new Shape(); }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    @Override
    Circle clone() { return new Circle(); }  // covariant
}

class ColoredCircle extends Circle {
    @Override
    ColoredCircle clone() { return new ColoredCircle(); }  // also covariant
}

ColoredCircle cc = new ColoredCircle().clone();  // returns ColoredCircle directly

This is commonly seen with the clone() method and in factory method patterns.

The instanceof operator in Java is a binary operator used to check whether an object is an instance of a particular class, subclass, or interface. It returns a boolean value.

SYNTAX:
object instanceof Type

Returns true if:
- object is a direct instance of Type
- object is an instance of a subclass of Type
- object implements the interface Type
- Type is a superclass/superinterface of object's class

Returns false if:
- object is not related to Type
- object is null

EXAMPLES:
String s = "Hello";
System.out.println(s instanceof String);  // true
System.out.println(s instanceof Object);  // true (String IS-A Object)
System.out.println(s instanceof Integer); // false (compiler warning — different hierarchies)

// With inheritance:
Animal a = new Dog();
System.out.println(a instanceof Animal);  // true
System.out.println(a instanceof Dog);     // true (actual object is Dog)
System.out.println(a instanceof Cat);     // false

// With interfaces:
List list = new ArrayList();
System.out.println(list instanceof List);       // true
System.out.println(list instanceof ArrayList);  // true
System.out.println(list instanceof RandomAccess);  // true (ArrayList implements it)

// null check:
Dog d = null;
System.out.println(d instanceof Dog);  // false (not an error)

USE CASE 1: SAFE DOWNCASTING
if (animal instanceof Dog) {
    Dog dog = (Dog) animal;  // safe — already checked
    dog.bark();
}

USE CASE 2: TYPE-BASED BEHAVIOR
public void processPayment(Payment payment) {
    if (payment instanceof CreditCardPayment) {
        CreditCardPayment cc = (CreditCardPayment) payment;
        cc.chargeWithCard();
    } else if (payment instanceof PayPalPayment) {
        PayPalPayment pp = (PayPalPayment) payment;
        pp.chargeWithPayPal();
    }
}

USE CASE 3: POLYMORPHIC COLLECTION PROCESSING
for (Object obj : mixedList) {
    if (obj instanceof String) {
        System.out.println("String: " + obj);
    } else if (obj instanceof Integer) {
        System.out.println("Integer: " + obj);
    }
}

JAVA 16+ PATTERN MATCHING FOR instanceof (more concise):
if (animal instanceof Dog dog) {  // declares dog variable automatically
    dog.bark();  // no explicit cast needed
}

// Instead of:
if (animal instanceof Dog) {
    Dog dog = (Dog) animal;
    dog.bark();
}

BEST PRACTICES:
- Prefer polymorphism over instanceof — instanceof often indicates poor OOP design
- Use instanceof primarily when working with legacy code or mixed-type collections
- Always check with instanceof before downcasting to prevent ClassCastException
- Pattern matching (Java 16+) is preferred over the traditional check-then-cast pattern

Constructor chaining is the process of calling one constructor from another constructor in Java. It ensures proper initialization of object state across the inheritance hierarchy.

RULES:
- this() calls another constructor in the SAME class
- super() calls a constructor in the IMMEDIATE PARENT class
- Both MUST be the FIRST statement in the constructor
- You cannot use both this() and super() in the same constructor
- If not specified, Java inserts super() (no-arg) automatically

EXAMPLE 1: CHAINING WITH this() IN THE SAME CLASS:
public class Student {
    String name;
    int id;
    String course;

    Student() {
        this("Unknown", 0, "None");  // calls the 3-param constructor
    }

    Student(String name) {
        this(name, 0, "None");  // calls the 3-param constructor
    }

    Student(String name, int id) {
        this(name, id, "None");  // calls the 3-param constructor
    }

    Student(String name, int id, String course) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
        this.course = course;
    }
}
// All constructors eventually delegate to the most-specific constructor.

EXAMPLE 2: CHAINING WITH super() IN AN INHERITANCE HIERARCHY:
class Person {
    String name;
    int age;

    Person() {
        super();  // calls Object's constructor (implicitly)
        this.name = "Unknown";
        this.age = 0;
    }

    Person(String name, int age) {
        super();  // calls Object's constructor
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
}

class Student extends Person {
    String course;

    Student() {
        super();  // calls Person()
        this.course = "None";
    }

    Student(String name, int age, String course) {
        super(name, age);  // calls Person(String, int)
        this.course = course;
    }
}

EXECUTION ORDER:
When new Student("Alice", 20, "CSC 282") is called:
1. Student(String, int, String) constructor starts
2. super(name, age) — calls Person(String, int)
3. Person constructor calls super() — calls Object()
4. Object() executes
5. Back to Person: name = "Alice", age = 20
6. Back to Student: course = "CSC 282"

So initialization happens from TOP to BOTTOM of the hierarchy.

WHY CHAINING MATTERS:
- Ensures parent class fields are initialized before child class fields
- Reduces code duplication (one main constructor, others delegate)
- Makes object construction predictable and consistent
- Required when parent class has no no-arg constructor (must use super(args))

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
class Vehicle {
    String type;

    Vehicle(String type) {
        this.type = type;
        System.out.println("Vehicle created: " + type);
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    String model;

    Car(String model) {
        super("Car");  // MUST call — Vehicle has no no-arg constructor
        this.model = model;
        System.out.println("Car model: " + model);
    }
}

new Car("Toyota");
// Output:
// Vehicle created: Car
// Car model: Toyota

Yes, a try block CAN exist without a catch block, but it MUST be followed by a finally block. You can have:
- try + catch (no finally)
- try + finally (no catch)
- try + catch + finally
- try-with-resources (auto-closes resources)

TRY-FINALLY (without catch):
Used when you want to ensure cleanup but don't want to handle the exception locally. The exception propagates up the call stack, but the finally block runs first.

public void readFile(String path) throws IOException {
    FileReader fr = null;
    try {
        fr = new FileReader(path);
        // read file
    } finally {
        // Always executes, even if exception occurs
        if (fr != null) {
            fr.close();  // cleanup
        }
    }
    // Exception propagates to caller — caller must handle IOException
}

FINALLY BLOCK EXECUTION GUARANTEE:
The finally block ALWAYS executes, EXCEPT when:
- System.exit(0) is called
- The JVM crashes
- The thread dies (deprecated Thread.stop())

Finally runs even:
- When a return statement is in try or catch
- When an exception is thrown
- When break/continue is used

DEMONSTRATION:
public static int testFinally() {
    try {
        System.out.println("In try");
        return 1;  // returns 1
    } finally {
        System.out.println("In finally — always runs!");
        // Runs BEFORE the value is returned
    }
}
// Output:
// In try
// In finally — always runs!
// Returns 1

DEMONSTRATION WITH EXCEPTION:
public static void testException() {
    try {
        System.out.println("In try");
        int x = 10 / 0;  // ArithmeticException
    } finally {
        System.out.println("Finally runs before exception propagates");
    }
    // Output:
    // In try
    // Finally runs before exception propagates
    // Then exception propagates up (uncaught)
}

TRY-FINALLY WITH RETURN IN FINALLY (special case):
public static int confusingFinally() {
    try {
        return 10;
    } finally {
        return 20;  // This overrides the try's return!
    }
}
// Returns 20, not 10!
// This is considered bad practice and confusing — avoid returning from finally

TRY-WITH-RESOURCES (Java 7+):
Automatically closes resources, effectively acting like try-finally for cleanup:

try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt");
     BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr)) {
    // use resources
} catch (IOException e) {
    // handle
}
// Resources are automatically closed (finally-like behavior built-in)

BEST PRACTICE:
- Use try-finally for cleanup when you don't want to handle the exception locally
- Use try-with-resources when available (cleaner, less error-prone)
- Never return from a finally block
- Keep finally blocks simple — just cleanup logic

Wrapper classes in Java are classes that encapsulate primitive data types into objects. Each primitive has a corresponding wrapper class in the java.lang package.

PRIMITIVE TO WRAPPER MAPPING:
Primitive | Wrapper Class | Example
----------|---------------|--------
byte      | Byte          | Byte b = 10;
short     | Short         | Short s = 100;
int       | Integer       | Integer i = 1000;
long      | Long          | Long l = 10000L;
float     | Float         | Float f = 3.14f;
double    | Double        | Double d = 3.14;
char      | Character     | Character c = 'A';
boolean   | Boolean       | Boolean bool = true;

WHY WRAPPER CLASSES EXIST:
1. Collections (ArrayList, HashMap, etc.) work only with objects, not primitives
   ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();  // valid
   ArrayList<int> list = new ArrayList<>();       // compile error

2. Generic types require objects, not primitives

3. Utility methods provided by wrapper classes:
   Integer.parseInt("123")      → 123 (int)
   Double.parseDouble("3.14")   → 3.14
   Integer.toString(123)        → "123"
   Integer.MAX_VALUE            → 2147483647
   Character.isDigit('5')       → true
   Character.isLetter('A')      → true

AUTOBOXING (Java 5+):
Automatic conversion of a primitive to its wrapper class by the compiler.

// Before Java 5 (manual boxing):
Integer i = Integer.valueOf(100);

// Java 5+ (autoboxing):
Integer i = 100;  // compiler inserts Integer.valueOf(100) automatically

AUTOBOXING EXAMPLES:
Integer x = 42;                  // int → Integer
Double d = 3.14;                 // double → Double
Boolean b = true;                // boolean → Boolean

list.add(42);                    // autoboxing: 42 → Integer.valueOf(42)
Map<String, Integer> map = ...;
map.put("score", 95);           // autoboxing: 95 → Integer.valueOf(95)

UNBOXING (Java 5+):
Automatic conversion of a wrapper object to its primitive type.

// Before Java 5 (manual unboxing):
int n = i.intValue();

// Java 5+ (autoboxing):
int n = i;  // compiler inserts i.intValue() automatically

UNBOXING EXAMPLES:
Integer x = 42;
int y = x;                        // unboxing: Integer → int

int sum = list.get(0) + list.get(1);  // unboxing then addition

if (b) { }                        // unboxing Boolean → boolean

PERFORMANCE NOTE:
Integer sum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    sum += i;  // autoboxing and unboxing on every iteration — inefficient!
}
// Each += does: sum = Integer.valueOf(sum.intValue() + i)
// Creates 1000 unnecessary Integer objects!

// Better:
int primitiveSum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    primitiveSum += i;
}
Integer sum = primitiveSum;  // single boxing at the end

NULL POINTER DANGER:
Integer x = null;
int y = x;  // NullPointerException — cannot unbox null to int

// Always check for null before unboxing:
if (x != null) {
    int y = x;
}

COMMON UTILITY METHODS:
Integer.parseInt("123");         // String → int
Integer.valueOf("123");          // String → Integer
Integer.toString(123);            // int → String
double d = Double.parseDouble("3.14");
String s = Double.toString(3.14);
boolean bool = Boolean.parseBoolean("true");

These methods handle the frequent task of converting between String and numeric types.

ArrayList is a class in the java.util package that implements the List interface using a dynamically resizable array. It is one of the most commonly used collection classes in Java.

ARRAY vs ARRAYLIST:

Feature          | Array                           | ArrayList
-----------------|---------------------------------|-------------------------
Size             | Fixed (declared at creation)     | Dynamic (auto-resizes)
Type             | Can hold primitives and objects   | Only objects (use wrapper)
Declaring        | int[] arr = new int[10];        | ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
Length           | arr.length (field)              | list.size() (method)
Access           | arr[0] (bracket notation)       | list.get(0) (method)
Assignment       | arr[0] = 5;                     | list.set(0, 5);
Adding           | Not possible after creation      | list.add(5);
Removing         | Not possible                     | list.remove(0);
Search           | Manual loop                      | list.contains(5);
Performance      | Faster (direct memory access)    | Slightly slower (method calls, resizing)
Generics         | Not supported                    | Fully supported

ARRAYLIST EXAMPLES:

Creating an ArrayList:
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();           // empty list
ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>(100);     // initial capacity 100
ArrayList<String> copy = new ArrayList<>(otherList);   // copy from another collection

Adding elements:
names.add("Alice");        // adds at end
names.add("Bob");
names.add(1, "Charlie");   // adds at index 1, shifts elements right

Accessing elements:
String first = names.get(0);           // "Alice"
String last = names.get(names.size() - 1);  // last element

Modifying elements:
names.set(1, "David");     // replace element at index 1

Removing elements:
names.remove(0);           // remove by index
names.remove("Bob");       // remove by object (first occurrence)
names.clear();             // remove all elements

Size and checking:
int size = names.size();
boolean empty = names.isEmpty();
boolean containsAlice = names.contains("Alice");
int index = names.indexOf("Alice");

Iteration:
// For loop:
for (int i = 0; i < names.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(names.get(i));
}

// Enhanced for-each loop:
for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println(name);
}

// ForEach with lambda (Java 8+):
names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));

// Iterator:
Iterator<String> it = names.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String name = it.next();
    if (name.equals("Bob")) it.remove();  // safe removal during iteration
}

COMMON ARRAYLIST METHODS:
- add(E element): append at end
- add(int index, E element): insert at position
- get(int index): return element at index
- set(int index, E element): replace at index
- remove(int index): remove by index, returns removed element
- remove(Object o): remove first occurrence, returns boolean
- size(): number of elements
- isEmpty(): check if empty
- contains(Object o): check if element exists
- indexOf(Object o): first index of element (-1 if not found)
- clear(): remove all elements
- toArray(): convert to array
- sort(Comparator): sort the list

INTERNAL WORKING:
ArrayList internally uses an Object[] array. When the array is full, it:
1. Creates a new array with ~50% larger capacity
2. Copies all elements from old array to new array
3. The old array becomes eligible for garbage collection

This makes add() O(1) amortized time, but occasional resizing is O(n).

ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();  // internal array size = 10 (default)
// After adding 10 elements, next add triggers resize to 15, then 22, etc.

JTextArea, JScrollPane, and JList are frequently used Swing components for text display and selection.

JTEXTAREA (Multi-line Text):
JTextArea is a Swing component that allows multi-line text display and editing.

// Creating JTextArea
JTextArea textArea = new JTextArea();
JTextArea textArea2 = new JTextArea("Initial text", 5, 30);  // 5 rows, 30 columns

// Common methods:
textArea.setText("Hello World");         // set text
textArea.append("\nNew line");           // append text
String content = textArea.getText();       // get all text
textArea.setEditable(false);              // read-only mode
textArea.setLineWrap(true);               // wrap long lines
textArea.setWrapStyleWord(true);          // wrap at word boundaries
textArea.setFont(new Font("Monospaced", Font.PLAIN, 12));

JSCROLLPANE (Scrollable Viewport):
JScrollPane provides scroll bars around a component. It is used with JTextArea, JList, JTable, or any component that may need scrolling.

// Wrapping JTextArea in JScrollPane:
JTextArea textArea = new JTextArea(20, 40);
JScrollPane scrollPane = new JScrollPane(textArea);
// Now textArea automatically gets scroll bars when content exceeds visible area

// Adding to frame/frame instead of adding textArea directly:
frame.add(scrollPane);  // NOT frame.add(textArea)

// Scroll pane policies:
JScrollPane sp = new JScrollPane(component,
    JScrollPane.VERTICAL_SCROLLBAR_AS_NEEDED,    // default — show when needed
    JScrollPane.HORIZONTAL_SCROLLBAR_AS_NEEDED);

// Options:
// ALWAYS, AS_NEEDED, NEVER

JLIST (Selectable List):
JList displays a list of items from which the user can select one or more items.

// Creating with String array:
String[] courses = {"CSC 281", "CSC 282", "CSC 283", "CSC 284"};
JList<String> list = new JList<>(courses);

// DefaultListModel (dynamic data):
DefaultListModel<String> model = new DefaultListModel<>();
model.addElement("Item 1");
model.addElement("Item 2");
JList<String> list = new JList<>(model);
model.addElement("Item 3");  // list updates automatically

// Selection mode:
list.setSelectionMode(ListSelectionModel.SINGLE_SELECTION);
// Also: SINGLE_INTERVAL_SELECTION, MULTIPLE_INTERVAL_SELECTION

// Getting selection:
String selected = list.getSelectedValue();         // single selection
int index = list.getSelectedIndex();
List<String> selectedItems = list.getSelectedValuesList();  // multi-selection

// Selection listener:
list.addListSelectionListener(e -> {
    if (!e.getValueIsAdjusting()) {  // filter intermediate events
        String value = list.getSelectedValue();
        System.out.println("Selected: " + value);
    }
});

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class StudentListApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Student List");
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setSize(400, 300);

        // List with model
        DefaultListModel<String> model = new DefaultListModel<>();
        model.addElement("Alice - CSC 282");
        model.addElement("Bob - CSC 281");
        model.addElement("Charlie - CSC 283");

        JList<String> studentList = new JList<>(model);
        studentList.setSelectionMode(ListSelectionModel.SINGLE_SELECTION);

        // Scroll pane for the list
        JScrollPane listScrollPane = new JScrollPane(studentList);

        // Text area for details
        JTextArea detailsArea = new JTextArea(5, 30);
        detailsArea.setEditable(false);
        JScrollPane textScrollPane = new JScrollPane(detailsArea);

        // Event handling
        studentList.addListSelectionListener(e -> {
            if (!e.getValueIsAdjusting()) {
                String selected = studentList.getSelectedValue();
                detailsArea.setText("Selected: " + selected);
            }
        });

        // Layout
        frame.setLayout(new BorderLayout());
        frame.add(listScrollPane, BorderLayout.CENTER);
        frame.add(textScrollPane, BorderLayout.SOUTH);

        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}

The File class in java.io represents a file or directory path in the file system. Important: it does NOT represent the file's content — it represents the path and provides methods to manage files and directories.

CREATING FILE OBJECTS:
File f1 = new File("C:\\data\\students.txt");    // absolute path (Windows)
File f2 = new File("/home/user/students.txt");      // absolute path (Unix)
File f3 = new File("students.txt");                 // relative path (current directory)
File f4 = new File("C:\\data", "students.txt");     // parent path + child name
File f5 = new File(new File("C:\\data"), "students.txt"); // File parent + child

PATH SEPARATORS:
- Windows: use \ (escape to \\) or use File.separator
- Better: use "/" — Java normalizes it to the platform separator

COMMON METHODS:

1. EXISTENCE AND TYPE:
f.exists()         // true if file/directory exists
f.isFile()          // true if it's a file (not directory)
f.isDirectory()     // true if it's a directory
f.isHidden()        // true if hidden file
f.canRead()         // true if readable
f.canWrite()        // true if writable

2. PATH INFORMATION:
f.getName()         // "students.txt"
f.getPath()         // path as specified in constructor
f.getAbsolutePath() // full absolute path
f.getParent()       // parent directory path (String)
f.getParentFile()   // parent directory as File object

3. FILE PROPERTIES:
f.length()          // file size in bytes
f.lastModified()    // last modification timestamp (long, epoch millis)

4. NAVIGATING DIRECTORIES:
File[] files = dir.listFiles();       // all files/subdirs
String[] names = dir.list();          // just names
FileFilter filter = f -> f.getName().endsWith(".txt");
File[] textFiles = dir.listFiles(filter);  // filtered

5. CREATING AND DELETING:
// Create empty file:
File f = new File("newfile.txt");
boolean created = f.createNewFile();  // returns false if already exists

// Create directory:
File dir = new File("data");
dir.mkdir();  // creates single directory, returns boolean

// Create nested directories:
File nested = new File("data\\2024\\students");
nested.mkdirs();  // creates all nonexistent parent directories

// Delete:
f.delete();  // returns boolean — file must exist
// For directories, must be empty first

// Rename:
File old = new File("old.txt");
File newName = new File("new.txt");
old.renameTo(newName);  // returns boolean

6. TEMPORARY FILES:
File temp = File.createTempFile("prefix", ".txt");
temp.deleteOnExit();  // deleted when JVM exits

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
public class FileDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File dir = new File("C:\\students");

        if (!dir.exists()) {
            dir.mkdir();
            System.out.println("Directory created");
        }

        File file = new File(dir, "roster.txt");
        if (!file.exists()) {
            try {
                file.createNewFile();
                System.out.println("File created: " + file.getAbsolutePath());
            } catch (IOException e) {
                System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Path: " + file.getPath());
        System.out.println("Size: " + file.length() + " bytes");
        System.out.println("Is file: " + file.isFile());

        // List directory contents
        if (dir.isDirectory()) {
            System.out.println("\nDirectory contents:");
            for (File f : dir.listFiles()) {
                System.out.println("  " + f.getName() + " (" + f.length() + " bytes)");
            }
        }
    }
}

NOTE: In Java 7+, java.nio.file.Path and java.nio.file.Files were introduced as a modern replacement for File, with better error handling, symbolic link support, and more features.

BufferedReader and BufferedWriter are wrapper classes in java.io that add buffering to character streams, significantly improving I/O performance.

WHY BUFFERING MATTERS:
Without buffering, each read/write operation goes directly to the underlying OS or device.
- Without BufferedReader: calling read() 1000 times = 1000 OS system calls (slow!)
- With BufferedReader: calling read() 1000 times = 1 OS system call for a buffer of 1000 chars, then 1000 reads from memory (fast!)

DECORATOR PATTERN:
Both classes follow the Decorator pattern — they wrap around another Reader/Writer to add functionality:

FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt");       // basic file reader
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);         // adds buffering

FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("output.txt");      // basic file writer
BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(fw);          // adds buffering
PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(bw);               // adds print methods

BUFFEREDREADER:
- Wraps a Reader (like FileReader, InputStreamReader)
- Default buffer size: 8192 characters (8KB)
- Key method: readLine() — reads a full line, returns null at EOF

// Reading line by line:
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("students.txt"));
String line;
while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
br.close();

// Reading from keyboard (System.in):
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
System.out.print("Enter name: ");
String name = br.readLine();
System.out.println("Hello, " + name);

// Reading all lines into a List (Java 8+):
List<String> lines = br.lines().collect(Collectors.toList());

Common methods:
- read(): read single character (int)
- read(char[] cbuf, int off, int len): read into array
- readLine(): read a line of text (returns null at EOF)
- lines(): stream of lines (Java 8+)
- skip(long n): skip characters
- close(): close and release resources

BUFFEREDWRITER:
- Wraps a Writer (like FileWriter, OutputStreamWriter)
- Default buffer size: 8192 characters (8KB)
- Key method: newLine() — writes platform-independent line separator (\n on Unix, \r\n on Windows)

// Writing with BufferedWriter:
BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("students.txt"));
bw.write("Student List");
bw.newLine();  // platform-independent line separator
bw.write("===========");
bw.newLine();
bw.write("Alice, 101, CSC 282");
bw.newLine();
bw.write("Bob, 102, CSC 281");
bw.newLine();
bw.close();

Common methods:
- write(String s): write a string
- write(char[] cbuf, int off, int len): write character array
- newLine(): write line separator
- flush(): force write buffer contents to underlying stream
- close(): flush and close

COMPARISON WITHOUT BUFFERING:
// SLOW — reads one character at a time from disk
FileReader fr = new FileReader("large.txt");
int ch;
while ((ch = fr.read()) != -1) {  // 1 OS call per character!
    // process ch
}

// FAST — reads 8KB at a time from disk, then serves from memory
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("large.txt"));
int ch;
while ((ch = br.read()) != -1) {  // 1 OS call per 8192 characters!
    // process ch
}

// COMBINING WITH TRY-WITH-RESOURCES:
try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
     BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("copy.txt"))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        bw.write(line);
        bw.newLine();
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}
// Both streams are automatically closed

FLUSHING:
BufferedWriter may hold data in its buffer. To ensure all data is written:
- Call flush() periodically (especially before long pauses)
- close() automatically flushes before closing

A transaction in SQL is a sequence of one or more SQL operations that are executed as a single unit of work. Either ALL operations succeed (commit) or NONE of them take effect (rollback).

ACID PROPERTIES:
- Atomicity: All operations in the transaction complete or none do
- Consistency: The database remains in a consistent state before and after the transaction
- Isolation: Concurrent transactions don't interfere with each other
- Durability: Once committed, changes persist even after system failure

JDBC TRANSACTION MANAGEMENT:

By default, each SQL statement in JDBC is executed in auto-commit mode — each statement is its own transaction. To group multiple statements into a single transaction:

1. DISABLE AUTO-COMMIT:
   conn.setAutoCommit(false);

2. EXECUTE SQL STATEMENTS:
   // All operations between setAutoCommit(false) and commit/rollback

3. COMMIT OR ROLLBACK:
   conn.commit();   // make all changes permanent
   // OR
   conn.rollback(); // undo all changes

EXAMPLE: BANK TRANSFER (classic transaction scenario):
Connection conn = null;
try {
    conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);
    conn.setAutoCommit(false);  // start transaction

    // Step 1: Deduct from sender
    String debitSQL = "UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - ? WHERE account_id = ?";
    PreparedStatement debitStmt = conn.prepareStatement(debitSQL);
    debitStmt.setDouble(1, 500.00);
    debitStmt.setInt(2, 1001);
    int rows1 = debitStmt.executeUpdate();

    // Check if sender has sufficient funds
    if (rows1 == 0) {
        throw new SQLException("Account 1001 not found");
    }

    // Step 2: Credit to receiver
    String creditSQL = "UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + ? WHERE account_id = ?";
    PreparedStatement creditStmt = conn.prepareStatement(creditSQL);
    creditStmt.setDouble(1, 500.00);
    creditStmt.setInt(2, 1002);
    int rows2 = creditStmt.executeUpdate();

    if (rows2 == 0) {
        throw new SQLException("Account 1002 not found");
    }

    // Both steps succeeded — commit
    conn.commit();
    System.out.println("Transfer successful");

} catch (SQLException e) {
    // Any error — rollback entire transaction
    if (conn != null) {
        try {
            conn.rollback();
            System.out.println("Transfer rolled back due to error");
        } catch (SQLException ex) {
            System.out.println("Rollback failed: " + ex.getMessage());
        }
    }
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
} finally {
    if (conn != null) {
        conn.setAutoCommit(true);  // restore default
        conn.close();
    }
}
// Either both accounts are updated, or neither is — never just one!

SAVEPOINTS (partial rollback):
Savapoints allow rolling back to a specific point within a transaction, not all the way.

try {
    conn.setAutoCommit(false);

    // First operation
    stmt.executeUpdate("INSERT INTO students VALUES(101, 'Alice')");

    Savepoint sp1 = conn.setSavepoint("after_insert");

    // Second operation
    stmt.executeUpdate("DELETE FROM students WHERE id = 999");

    // Oops, we need to undo just the delete
    conn.rollback(sp1);  // roll back to savepoint — insert is preserved!

    conn.commit();  // commit only the insert

} catch (SQLException e) {
    conn.rollback();  // full rollback
}

CONNECTION ISOLATION LEVELS:
conn.setTransactionIsolation(Connection.TRANSACTION_READ_COMMITTED);
- TRANSACTION_READ_UNCOMMITTED: lowest isolation, dirty reads possible
- TRANSACTION_READ_COMMITTED: prevents dirty reads (most databases default)
- TRANSACTION_REPEATABLE_READ: prevents dirty and non-repeatable reads
- TRANSACTION_SERIALIZABLE: highest isolation, prevents phantom reads (slowest)

BEST PRACTICES:
- Keep transactions as short as possible (don't include user think time)
- Always commit or rollback before closing the connection
- Use try-catch-finally or try-with-resources for proper cleanup
- Choose the appropriate isolation level (balance performance vs. data integrity)
- Test rollback scenarios to ensure data consistency

The == operator and the equals() method are both used for comparison in Java, but they work differently.

== OPERATOR:
- For PRIMITIVES: compares VALUES (int, double, boolean, char, etc.)
- For OBJECTS: compares REFERENCES (memory addresses) — do they point to the SAME object?

equals() METHOD:
- Defined in the Object class
- By default (in Object), it uses == — compares references
- Many classes override equals() to compare CONTENT or STATE
- String, Integer, Double, Boolean, Date, and all wrapper classes override equals()
- Custom classes should override equals() (and hashCode()) for logical equality

EXAMPLES:

PRIMITIVES:
int a = 5;
int b = 5;
System.out.println(a == b);  // true (values match)
// equals() cannot be used with primitives

STRING COMPARISON (commonly confused):
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
String s3 = new String("Hello");
String s4 = s1;

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // true (both reference the same String pool object)
System.out.println(s1 == s3);   // false (s3 is a different object in heap memory)
System.out.println(s1 == s4);   // true (same reference)

System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));  // true (same content "Hello")
System.out.println(s1.equals(s3));  // true (same content "Hello")

OBJECT COMPARISON:
Student s1 = new Student(101, "Alice");
Student s2 = new Student(101, "Alice");
Student s3 = s1;

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // false (different objects in memory)
System.out.println(s1 == s3);   // true (same reference)
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));  // depends on whether Student overrides equals()
                                    // If not overridden: false (uses Object's ==)
// Proper Student equals() override:
// public boolean equals(Object o) {
//     if (this == o) return true;
//     if (!(o instanceof Student)) return false;
//     Student s = (Student) o;
//     return this.id == s.id && this.name.equals(s.name);
// }

WRAPPER CLASS CACHING:
Integer x = 100;  // cached (-128 to 127)
Integer y = 100;
System.out.println(x == y);   // true (cached, same object)

Integer a = 200;  // not cached
Integer b = 200;
System.out.println(a == b);   // false (different objects)
System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true (same value)

// Moral: ALWAYS use .equals() for wrapper class comparison!

SUMMARY TABLE:
Scenario                  | ==                    | .equals()
--------------------------|-----------------------|--------------------------
Primitives (int, double) | Compares values       | N/A (cannot use)
String (same literal)     | true (pool)           | true (content)
String (new vs literal)   | false                 | true (content)
Custom objects (same)     | false (refs differ)   | true if overridden
Custom objects (not overridden) | false        | false (uses ==)
null vs object            | false                 | false (null.something = NPE)

BEST PRACTICE:
- Use == for primitives
- Use equals() for String and wrapper class comparison
- Override equals() in custom classes when logical equality is needed
- Always override hashCode() when overriding equals()
- Use Objects.equals(a, b) (Java 7+) for null-safe comparison

ENHANCED FOR LOOP (for-each):
Introduced in Java 5, the enhanced for loop simplifies iteration over arrays and collections.

SYNTAX:
for (Type element : iterable) {
    // use element
}

EXAMPLES:

// Array iteration:
int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for (int num : numbers) {
    System.out.println(num);
}

// ArrayList iteration:
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("Alice");
names.add("Bob");
names.add("Charlie");

for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println("Hello, " + name);
}

// Iterating over a Set:
Set<Integer> scores = new HashSet<>();
for (int score : scores) {
    System.out.println("Score: " + score);
}

// Iterating over a Map (entry set):
Map<String, Integer> grades = new HashMap<>();
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : grades.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + ": " + entry.getValue());
}

WHEN NOT TO USE for-each:
- When you need the index/counter
- When you need to remove elements during iteration (use iterator.remove())
- When you need to modify the array elements
- When iterating backwards

// Index needed — use traditional for:
for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(i + ": " + arr[i]);
}

VARARGS (Variable Arguments):
Varargs, introduced in Java 5, allows a method to accept zero or more arguments of the specified type.

SYNTAX:
returnType methodName(Type... parameterName)

Internally, varargs is treated as an array of the specified type.

EXAMPLES:

// Sum of any number of integers:
public static int sum(int... numbers) {
    int total = 0;
    for (int n : numbers) {
        total += n;
    }
    return total;
}

System.out.println(sum(1, 2));          // 3
System.out.println(sum(1, 2, 3, 4));    // 10
System.out.println(sum());              // 0 (empty call allowed)
System.out.println(sum(new int[]{1,2,3})); // can also pass array directly

// Printing multiple items:
public static void printAll(String... items) {
    for (String item : items) {
        System.out.println(item);
    }
}

printAll("A", "B", "C");
printAll();  // no arguments — prints nothing

// Varargs with other parameters:
public static void format(String prefix, String... suffixes) {
    System.out.print(prefix + ": ");
    for (String s : suffixes) {
        System.out.print(s + " ");
    }
}
// Varargs parameter MUST be the LAST parameter

// format("Names", "Alice", "Bob", "Charlie");  // OK
// format("Names");  // also OK (suffixes is empty)

// String.format uses varargs:
String result = String.format("Name: %s, Age: %d, GPA: %.2f", "Alice", 20, 3.85);

RULES:
1. A method can have only ONE varargs parameter
2. Varargs must be the LAST parameter in the method signature
3. The caller can pass zero or more arguments, or an array directly
4. Varargs can be overloaded, but ambiguity may occur

AMBIGUITY EXAMPLE:
void method(int... nums) { }
void method(int a, int... nums) { }

method(1, 2, 3);  // Which method? Both are candidates! (Compiler error)

VARARGS BEST PRACTICES:
- Use varargs for methods that logically accept zero or more items of the same type
- Document the method clearly (can pass array or individual elements)
- Be careful with overloading — avoid ambiguity
- Common JDK examples: String.format(), printf(), Arrays.asList()

Array.asList() uses varargs:
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C");
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

Copying binary files (images, audio, video, ZIP) requires byte stream I/O. The most efficient approach uses buffering with a byte array.

BASIC APPROACH (single byte — slow, for illustration only):
public static void copySingleByte(File source, File dest) throws IOException {
    try (FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(source);
         FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(dest)) {
        int b;
        while ((b = fis.read()) != -1) {  // reads one byte at a time — SLOW
            fos.write(b);                  // writes one byte at a time — SLOW
        }
    }
}
// Problem: For a 1MB file, this does 1 MILLION read/write calls!

BUFFERED STREAMS (byte array chunk — fast):
Best practice: read/write in chunks using a byte array buffer.

public static void copyWithBuffer(File source, File dest) throws IOException {
    byte[] buffer = new byte[8192];  // 8KB buffer
    int bytesRead;

    try (FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(source);
         FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(dest)) {

        while ((bytesRead = fis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
            fos.write(buffer, 0, bytesRead);  // write only the bytes actually read
        }
        System.out.println("File copied: " + source.getAbsolutePath());
    }
}
// For a 1MB file: ~128 read/write calls (8192 bytes each) vs 1 million!

USING BUFFERED STREAMS (alternative):
public static void copyBuffered(File source, File dest) throws IOException {
    try (BufferedInputStream bis = new BufferedInputStream(new FileInputStream(source));
         BufferedOutputStream bos = new BufferedOutputStream(new FileOutputStream(dest))) {

        byte[] buffer = new byte[4096];
        int bytesRead;
        while ((bytesRead = bis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
            bos.write(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
        }
        bos.flush();  // ensure remaining data is written
    }
}

COMPLETE UTILITY METHOD:
import java.io.*;

public class FileCopyUtility {

    public static void copyFile(File source, File dest) throws IOException {
        // Validation
        if (!source.exists()) {
            throw new FileNotFoundException("Source file not found: " + source);
        }
        if (source.isDirectory()) {
            throw new IOException("Source is a directory, not a file");
        }

        // Create parent directories if needed
        File parentDir = dest.getParentFile();
        if (parentDir != null && !parentDir.exists()) {
            parentDir.mkdirs();
        }

        // Copy with buffer
        try (FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(source);
             FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(dest)) {
            byte[] buffer = new byte[8192];
            int bytesRead;
            while ((bytesRead = fis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
                fos.write(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
            }
        }
    }

    // Overload for String paths
    public static void copyFile(String sourcePath, String destPath) throws IOException {
        copyFile(new File(sourcePath), new File(destPath));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            copyFile("C:\\photos\\vacation.jpg", "C:\\backup\\vacation.jpg");
            System.out.println("Copy successful");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Copy failed: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

MODERN APPROACH (Java 7+ with Files class):
import java.nio.file.*;

public static void copyWithNIO(Path source, Path dest) throws IOException {
    Files.copy(source, dest, StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);
}

// One-liner:
Files.copy(Paths.get("source.jpg"), Paths.get("dest.jpg"),
    StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);

The Files.copy() method uses the system's native file copy operation when possible (much faster for large files).

COMPARISON:
Method                          | Lines | Speed | Use Case
--------------------------------|-------|-------|---------
Single byte read/write          | 7     | Slow  | Never use
Buffered array (byte[] buffer)  | 12    | Fast  | General purpose
BufferedInputStream/OutputStream| 10    | Fast  | When streams are chained
Files.copy() NIO                | 1     | Fastest | Modern Java projects

JComboBox and JCheckBox are Swing components for user selection.

JCOMBOBOX (Drop-down List):
A JComboBox displays a drop-down list of items from which the user can select one.

// Creating JComboBox:
String[] courses = {"CSC 281", "CSC 282", "CSC 283", "CSC 284"};
JComboBox<String> courseBox = new JComboBox<>(courses);

// DefaultListModel (dynamic):
DefaultComboBoxModel<String> model = new DefaultComboBoxModel<>();
model.addElement("Item 1");
model.addElement("Item 2");
JComboBox<String> box = new JComboBox<>(model);

// Common methods:
courseBox.setSelectedIndex(0);     // select first item
courseBox.setSelectedItem("CSC 282");  // select by value
String selected = (String) courseBox.getSelectedItem();
int index = courseBox.getSelectedIndex();
courseBox.addItem("CSC 299");     // add item
courseBox.removeItem("CSC 281");  // remove item
courseBox.removeAllItems();       // clear all

// Editable combo box:
courseBox.setEditable(true);  // user can type custom value
String typed = courseBox.getEditor().getItem().toString();

// Event handling:
courseBox.addActionListener(e -> {
    String selected = (String) courseBox.getSelectedItem();
    System.out.println("Selected: " + selected);
});

// Or ItemListener:
courseBox.addItemListener(e -> {
    if (e.getStateChange() == ItemEvent.SELECTED) {
        System.out.println("Selected: " + e.getItem());
    }
});

JCHECKBOX (Checkbox):
A JCheckBox represents a boolean option that can be toggled on/off.

// Creating JCheckBox:
JCheckBox chkJava = new JCheckBox("Java");
JCheckBox chkPython = new JCheckBox("Python", true);  // initially selected
JCheckBox chkCpp = new JCheckBox("C++", false);

// Common methods:
chkJava.setSelected(true);           // check it
boolean isJava = chkJava.isSelected();  // true/false
chkJava.setEnabled(false);           // disable (grayed out)
chkJava.setText("Java Programming"); // change label

// Event handling:
chkJava.addActionListener(e -> {
    boolean selected = chkJava.isSelected();
    System.out.println("Java: " + (selected ? "checked" : "unchecked"));
});

// Or ItemListener:
chkJava.addItemListener(e -> {
    if (e.getStateChange() == ItemEvent.SELECTED) {
        System.out.println("Java checked");
    } else if (e.getStateChange() == ItemEvent.DESELECTED) {
        System.out.println("Java unchecked");
    }
});

WHEN TO USE EACH:

Use JComboBox when:
- There are MANY options (5+) — saves screen space
- Only ONE selection is allowed (mutually exclusive choices)
- You want a compact UI (e.g., selecting a semester, course, state, country)
- The list of options might change dynamically

Use JCheckBox when:
- There are FEW options (1-5) — each visible without clicking
- MULTIPLE selections are allowed (independent choices)
- It represents a boolean (yes/no) setting
- You want the user to see all options at a glance

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
JPanel panel = new JPanel(new GridBagLayout());

// Course selection (single — JComboBox)
panel.add(new JLabel("Course:"));
JComboBox<String> courseBox = new JComboBox<>(new String[]{
    "CSC 281", "CSC 282", "CSC 283"
});
panel.add(courseBox);

// Skill preferences (multiple — JCheckBox)
panel.add(new JLabel("Skills:"));
JCheckBox chkJava = new JCheckBox("Java");
JCheckBox chkSQL = new JCheckBox("SQL");
JCheckBox chkGUI = new JCheckBox("Swing");
panel.add(chkJava);
panel.add(chkSQL);
panel.add(chkGUI);

// Submit button
JButton submitBtn = new JButton("Submit");
submitBtn.addActionListener(e -> {
    String course = (String) courseBox.getSelectedItem();
    StringBuilder skills = new StringBuilder();
    if (chkJava.isSelected()) skills.append("Java ");
    if (chkSQL.isSelected()) skills.append("SQL ");
    if (chkGUI.isSelected()) skills.append("Swing ");
    System.out.println("Course: " + course + ", Skills: " + skills);
});
panel.add(submitBtn);

JRadioButton (alternative to JComboBox for few mutually exclusive options):
JRadioButton male = new JRadioButton("Male");
JRadioButton female = new JRadioButton("Female");
ButtonGroup genderGroup = new ButtonGroup();
genderGroup.add(male);
genderGroup.add(female);
// Only one can be selected (ButtonGroup enforces mutual exclusivity)
